<HEADLINE> Roundup: Federal Troops Press Ahead With Chechen Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Tuesday extended the
daily lull of its bombing of Grozny from six hours to eight to
allow civilians in the Chechen capital to flee as mop-up
operations continued in Shali, the fourth town in the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, federal forces kept up its artillery and aerial
raids at rebel positions in southern and eastern Chechnya Tuesday,
the Interfax news agency reported, citing a spokesman with the
Russian Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Grozny has been brought under siege for several days, but
federal forces have refrained from staging a frontal storming of
the city to avoid heavy military and civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
However, there were unconfirmed reports that some advance units
of federal troops were already inside Grozny, and Russian military
headquarters in the North Caucasus said no task has been set for
the troops to drive rebels out of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leaders pin their hopes in the defense of Grozny on
foreign mercenaries and gangsters who have committed grave crimes,
Interfax quoted Russian military sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Numerous gangsters are reportedly trying to break away from the
city and flee into the southern mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
The rebels "keep ethnic Russian inhabitants of Grozny as
hostages and do not let out of the city those who are prepared to
surrender to federal units," a Defense Ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
In Shali, which lies 20 kilometers southeast of Grozny, federal
"mop-up efforts have led to the arrest of 26 people suspected of
being Islamic militants and the discovery of arms and ammunition
depots, said Gennady Troshev, commander of a group involved in
Russia's Chechen campaign.
</P>
<P>
Several thousand militants remain in Grozny and most of them
are concentrated on the city's northwestern outskirts near the
Severny airport. They have mined western and southern approaches
to the city by laying highly toxic chemical substances and
preparing other explosives for detonation, Interfax reported,
citing military intelligence.
</P>
<P>
The current campaign was launched in September following
Chechen rebels' armed incursions into neighboring Daghestan and a
spate of terrorist bombings, also blamed on the rebels, that
killed about 300 people in Moscow and two other Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
As federal forces expand their control in Chechnya, the exodus
of refugees, initially numbering more than 260,000, has eased. So
far, some 43,000 of them have returned to their homes a spokesman
for the Russian Emergencies Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The supply of gas and power has been returning to the areas
liberated by federal forces. In addition, 57 schools and 10
hospitals have reopened.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Defense Ministry confirmed Tuesday
its loss of one Su- 25 attack plane and two helicopters over
Chechnya on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot of the Su-25, who ejected before the crash, has been
rescued to safety, but the two helicopters were brought down by
Chechen rebels in the rescue operation. The crew of one of the
helicopters perished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
