<HEADLINE> Jordanian FM, Russian Envoy Discuss Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
AMMAN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister
Abdul Ilah Khatib Tuesday met with visiting Russian Presidential
Envoy for Middle East Affairs Vasily Sredin on the latest
developments in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed developments on all tracks of peace
 talks, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel for a
permanent peace deal by next September are under way, while
negotiations between Israel and its another key foe Syria will
resume Wednesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Sredin, who is also Russia's deputy foreign minister,
expressed appreciation for  Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
and Jordan's efforts to help achieve a just and comprehensive peace
 in the region.
</P>
<P>
The envoy said Russia, a co-sponsor for the Middle East peace
 process besides the U.S., hoped to continue its consultations
with the kingdom over Middle East affairs.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the only two Arab states, besides Egypt,
that signed a peace treaty with Israel. For years, it has been
making efforts to help achieve a comprehensive and lasting peace in
 the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he extended an invitation to Khatib from Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov to visit Russia for talks on further
consolidating bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Khatib voiced Jordan's concern on the events
taking place in Chechenya and the dangers and pains confronting
civilians in the area.
</P>
<P>
But Khatib stressed Jordan's respect for the sovereignty of
the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
Sredin arrived in Amman Monday on a three-day visit on
bilateral ties and the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
