<HEADLINE> East Africa to Open School on Refugee Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Uganda and
Tanzania have approved the establishment of the East African
School on Refugees and Humanitarian Affairs (EASRHA) scheduled to
start in Dar es Salaam next month.
</P>
<P>
Members of the EASRHA's advisory board who convened at
University of Dar es Salaam (UDSM) Tuesday agreed that the school
would conduct short courses and long courses for undergraduate and
postgraduate.
</P>
<P>
According to the coordinator of the Center for the Study of
Forced Migration of UDSM Khoti Kamanga, the school is designed to
serve as a training forum for middle level personnel working in
government institutions, media and organizations dealing with
refugees in the Great Lakes region and the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Participants to the courses will be taught historical
evaluation of the refugee crisis, the international legal regime
of refugees, internally displaced persons' human rights and
international humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
Africa is home to 7.1 million or 34 percent of 21.1 million
refugees in the world and that Tanzania alone is currently hosting
at least 890,000 refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
