<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: America's Energy Appetite Rises Dramatically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The use of energy in the United
States has jumped dramatically in the last half-century. Energy
consumption increased by 194 percent from 1949 to 1998, although
the U.S. population grew only 82 percent, according to figures
from the U.S. Department of Energy, issued here on the sideline of
the U.S.-Africa Energy Ministers Conference, slated for December
13-15.
</P>
<P>
The analysis indicates that the average amount of energy used
by every American rose 62 percent during that period, while the
amount of energy required to produce a dollar's worth of goods and
services fell by 42 percent, said the Environment News Service (
ENS).
</P>
<P>
"Fifty years ago, the nation was nearly self-sufficient in
petroleum and was a net exporter of natural gas," said the "Annual
Energy Review" released by the Energy Information Agency, a
division of the federal Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
In 1948, "only 17 percent of our coal was used to produce
electricity and nuclear electricity was just a gleam in physicists
' eyes," the review said. Now, 90 percent of coal is burned to
generate electricity, and nuclear power accounts for one-fifth of
the electricity supply in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Industry was the largest consumer of energy in the economy in
1948, but its share dropped from almost half (46 percent) to 38
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
At the same time residential and commercial consumption of
energy has increased from 29 to 36 percent. The transportation
sector has edged up from 25 to 27 percent over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
U.S. energy was dominated by coal back in 1948, but coal has
given to natural gas and petroleum, although coal is still heavily
used to generate electricity in the nation.
</P>
<P>
In 1948, most U.S. homes used coal for heating, but now use of
coal in the home has become incidental.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power as a generator of electricity did not exist in
the U.S. until 1957, and it peaked in 1995 at 22 percent of
generation by utilities. Since 1990, the number of operable
nuclear reactors has declined as fewer new units came on line and
old units began to shut down.
</P>
<P>
Today nuclear power contributes about 10 percent to the nation'
s energy supply, the same amount as renewable sources, the Energy
Information Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Just as water power was relatively more important than wind
energy in preindustrial times, renewable energy today is dominated
by hydroelectric power. About half of the U.S. renewable total in
1998 came from hydroelectric power generation, which uses
damimpounded water to drive turbine generators that make
electricity.
</P>
<P>
Most of the rest of the U.S. renewable energy total came from
biomass, a diverse category that includes wood and wood waste,
methanol, and ethanol but also peat, wood liquors, wood sludge,
railroad ties, pitch, municipal solid waste, agricultural waste,
straw, tires, landfill gases, fish oils, and other things.
</P>
<P>
Geothermal energy was third in 1998, accounting for about five
percent of U.S. renewable energy production.
</P>
<P>
Solar energy (photovoltaic and thermal) contributes about one
percent to the renewable energy total while wind energy
contributes about 1.5 percent. About 90 percent of the solar
thermal collectors go to the residential sector. Ninety-three
percent of the collectors in the United States are used to heat
swimming pools, while seven percent are used for water heating and
less than one percent for space heating.
</P>
<P>
Prices for photovoltaic cells have edged down in recent years,
and the volume of shipments increased by a factor of 6.7 percent
between 1982 and 1997, the ENS report said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. wind energy production rose 89 percent between 1998 but
remains a very small factor in renewable energy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Energy's Annual Energy Outlook 1999
forecast, arrived at by the use of sophisticated computer
calculations suggests, "the near-term energy future will be one of
more: consumption, production, imports, and emissions."
</P>
<P>
Real energy prices are also expected either to increase only
modestly -- petroleum and natural gas -- or to decline -- coal and
electricity. These circumstances will encourage greater
consumption, and Annual Energy Outlook 1999 projects U.S. total
consumption to reach quadrillion Btu in 2020, 27 percent higher
than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Consumption is forecast to rise in all sectors. Growth is
predicted to be especially strong in transportation because of
more travel and greater freight requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
