<HEADLINE> Iran Seeks Foreign Investment to Finance Petrochemical Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran is seeking direct foreign
investment to finance petrochemical projects in the country's third
 five-year development plan (2000-2005), Managing Director of the
Petrochemical International Company Mohammad Hadi Rahbari said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Islamic Republic News Agency, Rahbari said Iran
has planned to carry out olefin series projects (8-9-10), aromatic-
4 and methanol-4, which require 5 billion U.S. dollars foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
The olefin-8 project will be carried out at Imam Khomeini port
in southern Iran,and the olefin-9, olefin-10, aromatic-4 and
methanol-4 projects will be established in the Asaluyeh special
industrial zone in Bushehr province, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rahbari said his company has entered into negotiations with
foreign companies to attract 2-2.5 billion dollars to implement the
 olefin-8 and olefin-9 projects.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are underway between Iran and the German company
Alenac to set up a light polyethylene plant, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added some 1.7 billion foreign credits were used in carrying
out the petrochemical projects in the first five-year development
plan (1989-1994) and 95 percent of the credits, which had to be
paid back in a five-year term, has been repaid so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
