<HEADLINE> Security Council to Vote on New Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Britain on Tuesday once again push the United Nations Security
Council to vote on a new comprehensive policy towards Iraq in a
bid to revive U.N. weapons inspection in the country.
</P>
<P>
The vote has been postponed for several days amid sharp
division among the members of the Security Council and the United
States and Britain did not want to see the draft resolution being
killed.
</P>
<P>
U.N. diplomats said some changes in the draft text have been
made over the night after consultations among capitals of the five
permanent members of the Council, namely China, Russia, France.
Britain and the United States, and they refused to give any
details.
</P>
<P>
A resolution needs nine positive votes and no vetoes from the
Council's five permanent members for adoption and the result of
the vote is still uncertain, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution seeks to create a new arms regime for Iraq
to replace the United Nations Special Commission in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction who has been barred
from returning to Iraq since the U.S.-led military strikes against
the country last December.
</P>
<P>
It, if adopted, would immediately lift the ceiling on how much
oil Iraq could sell in every six months under the oil-for-food
program which began to be implemented in late 1996 aimed to ease
the humanitarian crisis in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has reiterated that it would reject the resolution as an
American attempt to hide its "evil intentions."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
