<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: Russia Needs No International Help in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia does not need help from
international organizations in resolving the conflict in Chechnya,
Russian First Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander Avdeyev said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, made in Makhachkala, regional capital of
Daghestan, came after OSCE chairman Knut Vollebaek's offer to
mediate between federal authorities and the Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe could
use its international influence in aiding Russia's anti-terrorist
operation in Chechnya by calling on all countries not to support
Chechen terrorists, Avdeyev said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a lack of go-betweens in the conflict but the
absence of an influential Chechen who could hold talks on behalf
of the republic," he said. "We feel that our colleagues in the
West underestimate the danger of terrorism. Our units in Chechnya
are defending the whole of Europe from the danger of terrorism as
well as Russia's integrity."
</P>
<P>
Avdeyev is accompanying Vollebaek, who is also Norwegian
Foreign Minister, in his North Caucasus tour, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek urged the Chechen rebels and the Russian authorities
to stop fighting and settle the conflict under OSCE mediation.
</P>
<P>
Russia launched the current military campaign against Chechen
rebels in September following their armed incursion into
neighboring Daghestan and a spate of terrorist bombings, also
blamed on the rebels, that killed about 300 people in Moscow and
two other Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Vollebaek visited Daghestan's Botlikh district,
which was attacked by Chechen militants last summer.
</P>
<P>
He said he had seen the plight of civilians in Botlikh and
would like to urge the rebels and the Russian authorities to stop
military operations.
</P>
<P>
He said the OSCE is ready to join the effort to settle the
Chechen conflict at any moment.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE is an organization that has no armed forces of its own
and only has moral weight, and can act only on at the request of
the member-states, Vollebaek said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
