<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Institutes Predict Upswing of German Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 14 (Xinhua)--Three major German economic
research institutes Tuesday predicted in their reports a strong
upswing for the country's economy in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
The Kiel World Economic Institute, the Hamburg Economic
Institute and the Institute for Economic Research in Halle all
concluded that German economy was ending its weak phase and was
set for robust expansion.
</P>
<P>
The projections of economic growth for the largest European
economy next year ranged between 1.5 per cent and 2.5 per cent in
reports of the three institutes.
</P>
<P>
The Hamburg institute said that the economic downturn in
Germany, triggered by the worldwide financial turbulence since
year 1997, was now "largely overcome."
</P>
<P>
In addition, the drop of the euro's exchange rate had clearly
boosted the competitiveness of German firms in overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
The three institutes foresaw a decline in joblessness next year,
although they said the job market improvement would largely be
confined in western Germany.
</P>
<P>
With prices expected to remain relatively stable and wage
agreements projected to show modest 2.2 per cent in pay rise,
Germany can also expect higher capacity utilization and
productivity next year, the three institutes' reports showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
