<HEADLINE> Denktash Says Cyprus Peace Talks to Resume Early Nest Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Rauf Denktash, the
leader of the Turkish Cypriots, said on Tuesday that the next
round of Cyprus peace talks would resume in late January, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Denktash made the remarks after he finished his final talks
with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan this morning.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Denktash said he would be back in late
January.
</P>
<P>
Denktash and Glafcos Clerides, President of Cyprus and the
leader of the Greek Cypriots began the "proximity talks" on
December 3 and the talks are expected to conclude today.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. brokered "proximity talks" mean that the two parties
are within reach but do not meet face to face.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been virtually divided since troops from Turkey
occupied the north of the island in 1974 in reaction to a coup in
Nicosia engineered by the junta then ruling Greece.  
</P>
</TEXT>
