<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Sets New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The deficit in the current account, the broadest measure of
foreign trade, jumped by 11.2 percent in the third quarter this
year, up from 80.9 billion dollars in the second quarter, the
Department reported.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the current account deficit is running at an
annual rate of 319 billion dollars, 45 percent higher than last
year's 220 billion dollars imbalance.
</P>
<P>
The current account includes not only trade in goods and
services, but also investment flows and spending on foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
For the third quarter, the deficit in goods rose to 92.1
billion dollars, up from 84.4 billion dollars in the second
quarter. U.S exports of capital goods, including civilian aircraft,
were up by 4.6 percent but imports increased an even faster 6.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Three-fourths of the gain in imports reflected widespread gains
in manufactured goods while one-fourth of the increase was blamed
on a higher foreign petroleum bill, reflecting rising prices. The
government had earlier reported in its monthly trade figures that
foreign oil prices in September climbed to the highest level in
two years.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in services, such as airline fares and other types
of travel expenses, dropped to 18.3 billion dollars in the July-
September quarter, compared to 19.3 billion dollars in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in investment flows widened to 4.9 billion dollars
in the third quarter, compared to 4.6 billion dollars in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The category that includes foreign aid, known as net unilateral
transfers, was unchanged in the third quarter at 11.2 billion
dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
