<HEADLINE> Mideast Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
 from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Some 220,000 Israelis were out of job in October
this year, representing 9.2 percent of the national work force,
according to figures announced by Israel's Central Bureau of
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in October was almost at the same level
recorded in August and September. In August, the unemployment rate
was 9 percent while that for September was 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM --Israeli National Infrastructure Minister Eli Suissa
 has ruled out the possibility importing water from Turkey to help
solve Israel's water shortage, after studying a report prepared by
a local water company.
</P>
<P>
The Mekorot Water Company said in its report that bringing
water from Turkey will be most costly than purifying water locally.
</P>
<P>
Israel is facing water shortage due to the dry weather and the
government has been studying the possibility of importing water
from Turkey for some time.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Tourism Ministry said Tuesday that in
October this year, 282,200 foreign tourists visited Israel, the
highest monthly figure recorded since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Between January and October, 2.09 million foreign tourists
visited Israel. Of those, 1.478 million arrived by air.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Transport Ministry plans to issue
international tenders seeking bids for a light-rail system in
Jerusalem and another one in Haifa. A tender for light train system
 for Jerusalem is expected within a few days, while a tender for
the planning of the Haifa system is expected within three months.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Basaran Ulusoy, chairman of the Turkish Association of
 Travel Agencies, said that Turkey's tourism revenue will increase
by 3-4 billion dollars due to the European Union's decision last
Friday to grant the country candidacy for membership.
</P>
<P>
Ulusoy said Turkey's existing tourism industry infrastructure
was sufficient to accommodate more tourists, and it was not
necessary to increase new investment to catch up with rising
demand, Turkish Daily News reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Economy Minister Recep Onal urged investors to
 buy stocks if they want to make profits, saying the government has
 paved the way for substantial gains in the country's financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
Onal said "our recent banking arrangements seek to curb the cost
 of borrowing, which is two high in Turkey compared with other
countries," Turkish Daily News reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Once the government's new arrangements have yielded results, the
 production sector will be able to have access to resources at
reasonable costs, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
