<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Rise Slightly in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said
Tuesday that consumer prices increased just 0.1 percent in
November, the best showing in five months.
</P>
<P>
The gain in the Consumer Price Index, the most closely watched
inflation gauge, followed a 0.2 percent rise in October, the
Department reported.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, consumer inflation has been rising at an
annual rate of 2.7 percent, compared with a 1.6 percent increase
in 1998, but all of the acceleration has reflected higher energy
costs.
</P>
<P>
If excluding the volatile energy and food categories, prices
were up by 0.2 percent, leaving the "core" rate of inflation
rising at a more moderate rate of 2 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve meets next week to decide whether to raise
interest rates again this year. Today's report on consumer prices
could ease concerns among economists and investors about a
potential outbreak of inflation. Financial markets will be looking
closely at the report for any clues as to what the Fed will do to
interest rates in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that clothing prices dropped by 0.5 percent
in November after posting sharp rises in the two previous months.
</P>
<P>
Overall energy prices were flat in November, reflecting falling
prices for gasoline and electricity and rising prices for fuel oil
and natural gas. Gasoline prices fell by 0.6 percent and
electricity prices decreased by 0.2 percent. But fuel oil jumped
by 2.6 percent and natural gas by 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last month, crude oil surged to its highest point since January
1991, when the Persian Gulf war drove up prices.
</P>
<P>
Production limits by oil-producing nations and increased demand
from recovering economies in Asia and from consumers preparing for
the winter accounted for the increase in some energy costs,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In November, food prices rose a slim 0.1 percent, the best
showing since June. A 3 percent decline in the price of vegetables
helped offset rising prices for pork, poultry and fruits.
</P>
<P>
Transportation prices were flat last month as new-car prices
held steady and airline fares rose by 0.7 percent, an improvement
over the 5.3 percent increase posted in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan's FM Resigns in Discord With President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Sudan's Foreign Minister
Mustafa Ismail has resigned to protest against President Omar al-
Bashir's declaration of a state of emergency, a spokesman for the
ruling National Congress Party (NCP) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Mohamed Al-Hassan Al-Amin, added that other
ministers from the party were also expected to extend their
resignations.
</P>
<P>
Ismail's resignation came amid a political crisis that stemmed
from a power struggle between the president and the National
Assembly (parliament) Speaker Hassan al Turabi.
</P>
<P>
After El-Bashir declared a three-month state of emergency and
dissolved the parliament Sunday, the NCP said the president was
automatically disqualified from the party for violating its rules.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said Bashir took such measures in a bid to
prevent the parliament from meeting on Tuesday to pass legislation
curbing presidential powers to appoint and dismiss provincial
governors.
</P>
<P>
First Vice President Ali Osman Mohammed Taha, government
spokesman Ghazi Salah Eddin Attabani and six ministers in the 25-
member cabinet have publicly supported Bashir's actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
