<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toronto Stock Exchange Breaks 8,000-point Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Toronto Stock Exchange (TSE)
300-stock composite index climbed above the 8000 mark for the
first time Monday, propelled by Nortel Networks Corp and other hi-
tech giants.
</P>
<P>
The index drifted around the mile-stone mark until buying
petered out to finish at a close of 7,989.91, up 35.32 points or 0.
44 percent on the day, the Globe and Mail Newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Still the record was hailed a "bloody time" by leading
technical analysts, according the daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
A number of Canadian stocks hit 52-week highs, including Nortel,
which saw 60 cents (about 0.41 U.S. dollars) up to an all-time
high of 131.10 Canadian dollars (about 88.75 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications colossus BCE Inc., which owns 40 percent of
Nortel, followed with a gain of 1.75 Canadian dollars (about 1.18
U.S. dollars to hit its own record of 115 dollars (about 77.86 U.S.
dollars
</P>
<P>
Montreal-based Telesystem International Wireless Inc. gained 7.
25 dollars (about 4.91 U.S. dollars) to reach a new high of 48
dollars(about 32.50 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
