<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Attaches Great Importance to Energy Development in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, the United States, December 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S.
State Department official Tuesday told some 50 African energy
ministers here that the Clinton Administration is attaching great
importance to the energy development in Africa, which is rich in
both natural and human resources.
</P>
<P>
Susan Rice, assistant secretary of state for African affairs,
made the statement at the plenary session of the U.S-Africa Energy
Ministers Conference scheduled for December 13-15.
</P>
<P>
"This conference is testimony to how far we have to come over
the past few years. Africans and Americans, public and private
sectors, strive to build stronger ties and true partnership
between Africa and America," she said.
</P>
<P>
Rice outlined two major goals in the U.S. Africa policy: to
accelerate Africa's full integration into the global economy, and
to combat transnational security concerns such as terrorism,
proliferation, environmental degradation and diseases.
</P>
<P>
At present, "Americans are depending increasingly on Africa,
one of the world's most untapped energy markets, to fuel cars, to
heat living rooms and to power industry," she said. "Americans are
working hard to be both investors and consumers of African energy.
"
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the United States imported some 1.4 million barrels
of oil a day from Africa, accounting for some 17 percent of the
nation's total oil imports, in comparison to 23 percent of oil
imports from the oil-rich Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Rice said that the U.S. government, while turning to Africa as
an important source of U.S. energy, vowed to keep a good balance
between the energy development and environmental preservation in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
She cited an example to show how the Clinton Administration is
taking Africa seriously, saying that "five years ago, Africa was
nearly with the domain of a bureau under the State Department, and
the other is USAID. But now the Department of Energy, the
Department of Transportation and the Department of Commerce are
all proposing new initiatives to strengthen the U.S. relationship
with Africa."
</P>
<P>
"Under President (Bill) Clinton's Partnership Plan, the
Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) has dedicated three-
quarters of a billion dollars to encourage private investment in
Africa" to promote development, technical assistance and improve a
high-level dialogue on the cooperation between Africa and America,
she said.
</P>
<P>
"Roughly 30 African countries are liberalizing their trade
regimes, reducing tariffs, ending subsidies and fighting
corruption," she said, adding that African regional groups, such
as the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and the
Economic Community for West African States (ECOWAS) are also
playing an important role in the process.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the open plenary session, Bill Richardson, U.
S. secretary of energy, said that "energy is our future."
</P>
<P>
The United States, the economic superpower in the world, is
seeking African energy resources, oil and natural gas in
particular, to ensure its energy security at the turn of the
century as most African energy ministers agree that "energy is the
tool for development." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
