<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama, U.S. Sign Canal Handover Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Panama and the United
States signed Tuesday the historical document of understanding by
which the Panama Canal is reverted to Panama after 85 years of U.S.
administration.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of notes was signed by Panamanian President Mireya
Moscoso and former U.S. president Jimmy Carter on behalf President
Bill Clinton, who excused himself from attending the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The document was immediately signed by the King Juan Carlos of
Spain, who attended the ceremony together with Queen Sofia.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of the Latin American countries also signed the
document that will bear witness for the future generations of the
end of colonialism in Panama and Latin America during the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico, Andres Pastrana of
Colombia, and Hugo Banzer of Bolivia, joined as witnesses of honor
in the signing of the agreement that guarantees Panama's total
sovereignty over the canal.
</P>
<P>
The main political leaders of the government and of the
opposition have stated their desire of working together for the
security and the efficiency of the interoceanic waterway in the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The formal delivery of the canal will be held December 31,1999,
in compliance with the Torrijos-Carter treaties of 1977,that
guaranteed the total withdrawal of the U.S. forces before the year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
