<HEADLINE> S. Leone to Miss Disarmament Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone will miss the
December 15 deadline of disarming the country's 45, 000 civil war
combatants, as designated by the Lome peace accord signed in July,
an official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This will not be accomplished due to delays and mistrust among
parties involved in implementation of the peace process," Sierra
Leone's Information Minister Julius Spencer said in the capital
Freetown, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the national committee dealing with
disarmament would meet on Wednesday to review the situation "and
take further measures to speed up the program".
</P>
<P>
To enforce the hardly-earned peace in the west African country,
the United Nations started deploying contingents of a planned
6,000-strong peacekeeping force from the end of last month.
Soldiers from India and Kenya have arrived to join a larger force
of the Nigerian-led West Africa Peacekeeping Force or ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord, signed by President Tejan Kabbah and his
rebel foes to end a nine-year conflict, set December 15 for the
completion of demobilization of fighters of all sides.
</P>
<P>
However, hard core units of Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front
remain armed and continue clashes with followers of former junta
leader Johnny Koroma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
