<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Opposition Claims Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's main opposition
party, the former rebel movement Renamo (Mozambique National
Resistance), on Tuesday claimed victory in the country's general
elections, but according to the law, the official results should
be announced by the National Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
At a Maputo press conference, the spokesperson for the Renamo
election office, Gulamo Jafar, issued what he called "official
results and projections" showing that Renamo leader Afonso
Dhlakama will win the presidency, and Renamo will be the largest
party in the next parliament.
</P>
<P>
Renamo projected that Dhlakama will win between 51.3 and 52.5
percent of the presidential vote, while the incumbent, Joaquim
Chissano with some 47.5 to 48.7 percent. Taimo Jamisse,
chairman of the election commission, said that Renamo must assume
full responsibility for its declaration, adding that the
commission will publish the final results sometime later.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique held its second multi-party presidential and
parliamentary elections on December 3-5 since 1994, which the
international observers regarded as free and fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
