<HEADLINE> 2 Lebanese Civilians Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Two Lebanese civilians were
wounded Wednesday in military clashes between Israeli forces and
Lebanese guerrillas, security sources said.
</P>
<P>
A woman was injured when the Beit Yahoun Bayada village in which
 she lived inside the Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon
 was hit by Israeli shells, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Another man was seriously wounded when shells hit his car in
Zawtar Sharqia village.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, said in a
statement that its fighters had launched a series of attacks on
Israeli posts, causing direct hit on their targets.
</P>
<P>
In response, Israeli warplanes blasted villages and hills on the
 verge of the border zone which are believed as the hideouts of
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust the Israeli occupation troops
out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
