<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most of Angolans Live in Poverty: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Seventy percent of the Angola's
12.6 million people are living below the poverty line, a report
issued by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP office in Angola said in the report that destructive
civil war and the remnant colonist impact have dragged most
Angolans into dire penury, Angola's official news agency ANGOP
reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Angolan government has failed to achieve
its objectives for stabilizing and rehabilitating the economy in
1998-2000, mainly due to the renewed civil conflicts in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
Although the rebels of the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) have fled into forest areas, the
Angolan people can not yet expect an immediate peace, it added.
</P>
<P>
Without peace, the Angolan government has to fight against the
rebels instead of leading a campaign against the poverty,
stabilizing the economic and social situation, and improving the
welfare of the Angolan people.
</P>
<P>
Angola, as a country enjoying abundant natural resources such
as diamond and petroleum reserves, has great potential to develop
its economy and improve the human development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
