<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Plans to End Chechen War By March: General Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia plans to end its anti-
terrorist operations in the breakaway republic of Chechnya by the
end of February next year, said a top Russian military official
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It will "take another two to three months" to eliminate the
militants in Chechnya, said General Valery Manilov, first deputy
chief of the Russian Armed Forces' General Staff, at a meeting
with foreign military attaches at the General Staff Academy.
</P>
<P>
He said about 12,000 to 15,000 militants have remained in
Chechnya, including some 2000 terrorists and bandits backed by
foreign extremists, adding that "this terrorist army will have to
be eliminated unless the bandits surrender and lay down their arms.
"
</P>
<P>
Manilov said the federal troops would liberate Grozny, capital
of Chechnya, and he promised that "no massive attacks or storming
of Grozny will be launched while even one civilian remains."
</P>
<P>
Now the Russian troops control over 60 percent of Chechnya's
territory in which about 90 percent of the Chechen population
were living.
</P>
<P>
"A total of 120 Chechen villages have been cleared of militant
formations. Particularly the flat territory of Chechnya has been
completely freed of bandits and terrorists," Manilov said.
</P>
<P>
The militants are fortifying their positions in sparsely
populated mountainous and semi-mountainous areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Russian troops freed the second biggest Chechen
city of Gudermes and three other key Chechen towns of Argun, Urus-
Martan and Shali, completing the surrounding of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Russia began its military operations in Chechnya in late
September after Chechen rebels' armed incursions into the
neighboring republic of Dagestan and a spate of apartment building
blasts that claimed over 300 people in Moscow and two other
Russian cities. The Russian authorities blamed Chechen extremists
for planning and carrying out terrorist acts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Submits Draft Budget to Majlis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Wednesday submitted a draft national budget of 358.777
billion rials (about 119.59 billion U.S. dollars) for the coming
year to the Majlis (parliament) for approval.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Majlis, Khatami said the budget for the new
Iranian calendar year (starting March 21, 2000) shows an increase
of 29.9 percent from that of the current year.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total amount, 125.953 billion rials (about 41.98
billion dollars) is allocated to the government budget and the rest
 to the budget for organizations and profit-making institutes
affiliated to the government and banks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government budget shows a 14.8 percent increase
 compared to this year's budget while the budget for organizations
and profit-making institutes enjoys a 30.8 growth, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that the government's income is estimated at 110.
395 billion rials (about 36.80 billion dollars), showing a 16.1
percent increase from this year's figure.
</P>
<P>
He said that out of the amount 31 percent are tax incomes, 49
percent oil revenues and 20 percent other incomes.
</P>
<P>
The budget put the current expenditure at 80.849 billion rials
(about 26.95 billion dollars) with a growth of 26.3 percent and the
 development expenses at 24.670 billion rials (about 8.22 billion
dollars) with a 20 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
He said that the credits allocated to judicial fairs have risen
by 61.5 percent, to preservation of order and security by 54.5
percent, to defense affairs by 31 percent and social security 50
percent compared to what had been predicted for the current year.
</P>
<P>
Khatami noted that in the next year budget, priority has been
given to implementation of special job-creating projects, and
necessary mechanisms have been predicted to support investment on
small industries and job creating groups in the form of
cooperatives and self-employment units.
</P>
<P>
The credits predicted for payment of subsidies on basic
commodities with a growth of 19.6 percent will be equal to 7.950
billion rials (about 2.65 billion dollars) for the next year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami noted that the present subsidy payment system for basics
 has some flaws and the government believes any other alternative
depends on finding suitable mechanisms to protect the low-income
groups and prevent damage to the society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
