<HEADLINE> Partial Oromo Military Officials Based in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The first flight of Oromo
military officials have left Somalia in accordance with an
agreement signed between Somali faction leader Hussein Mohamed
Aidid and the Ethiopian government.
</P>
<P>
Among them are General Waqow Gudow, main commander of the Oromo
 Liberation Front (OLF) fighters based in southern Somalia, and
eight other senior military commanders.
</P>
<P>
They left the Ballidogleh airport, 90 kilometers south of
Mogadishu, Tuesday, diplomats in Mogadishu said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Since early in the year, hundreds of OLF fighters together
with their weapons and ammunition had arrived in southern Somalia,
making the war torn nation of somalia just another battlefield for
Ethiopia-Eritrea confrontation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the offices of the OLF fighters in
Mogadishu had been closed down with the presence of Libyan and
Egyptian diplomats as a move to implement the first part of the
agreement signed by Aidid and the Ethiopian government on October
27 this year.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Libya and Egypt, the brokers of the
agreement, were mandated by the Arab League to supervise the
demilitarization of the border areas between southern Somalia and
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Most of the OLF fighters have crossed to Ethiopia months before
the agreement was signed so as to fight against the forces of
Addis Ababa regime of Prime Minister Meles Zenawi.
</P>
<P>
There are still 108 former military personnel from the OLF in
southern Somalia. However, this force had been disarmed with the
supervision of the Libyan and Egyptian diplomats and they are now
living as ordinary Somali civilians.
</P>
<P>
Some of them have already reported to have engaged in managing
small farms of their own in Lower Shabelleh region, while others
are living as refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to officials of Aidid, the departure of the Oromo
officials has concluded the fulfillment of their side on the
agreement reached in the Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
