<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Nearing Goal of Localizing Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Macao has basically realized the
localization of laws so far, but another more than 20 technical
regulations including two important laws, the Labor Procedural
Code and Tax Procedural Code, which still need to be localized, a
Macao government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Sam Chan Io, coordinator of the Law Translation Office of the
Macao government, said at a press conference today that Macao has
basically completed the localization of laws with the localization
of important codes, accessory codes and the drafting of new laws
by the Legislative Assembly to replace old laws.
</P>
<P>
Laws localized so far include five basic codes in Macao, namely
Criminal Code, Criminal Procedural Code, Civil Code, Civil
Procedural Law and Commerce Code, and some other major codes
concerning notarization, registration, administrative procedures
and industrial property.
</P>
<P>
Localization of laws, localization of civil servants and the
official status of the Chinese language are three major issues
concerning the smooth transition and transfer of power in Macao,
which is to return to China on Dec. 20 after being ruled by the
Portuguese for more than 150 years.
</P>
<P>
Sam Chan Io said the basic goal of localizing the laws in Macao
is to have laws that address local conditions, meet with the need
in modern times, and are drafted in both Chinese and Portuguese
languages.
</P>
<P>
Laws in Macao derive from the law system on the European
continent, with most of them originated in Portugal and drafted in
Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
Sam Chan Io said the translation of the Macao laws into Chinese,
as an important part of the work in localizing laws, has been
completed, with the Macao government publicizing the Chinese
version of 76 laws by September this year.
</P>
<P>
All these laws were drafted between 1976 and 1992, since all
laws drafted after 1992 are in both Chinese and Portuguese
languages, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Although about 20 technical regulations still need to be
localized to achieve the final localization of laws, the goal has
been basically reached since these regulations are not very
important, Sam said.
</P>
<P>
Sam also pointed out that Macao will continue to absorb new
ideas from Portugal on law interpretation after its return to
maintain the vitality of the local laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
