<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weizman Urges Religious Party to Support Peace with Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer
Weizman Wednesday urged a powerful ultra-Orthodox religious party
in the ruling coalition to support the effort by Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to reach a peace agreement with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Weizman made the appeal during his meeting with Eli Yishai,
leader of the Shas party, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Holding 17 seats in the Knesset (parliament), Shas is a key
partner in Barak's coalition, which enjoys a 68-seat majority in
the 120-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
Barak chose Shas as a coalition partner after winning a general
election in May mainly because he wanted to garner as much as
support for his peace policy with Israel's Arab neighbors. Shas
holds a moderate position in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But the party abstained in a parliamentary vote Monday over
Barak's policy statement on the renewed peace talks with Syria. As
a result, Barak only won a narrow majority in the parliament over
his statement.
</P>
<P>
Barak will hold talks with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-
Sharaa in Washington later Wednesday, resuming the negotiations
between the two sides after nearly four years of suspension.
</P>
<P>
Without the support of Shas, any peace agreement Barak reached
with Syria would not be approved by the parliament since Israeli
laws stipulate that an agreement with Syria must be supported by an
 absolute majority of 61 legislators.
</P>
<P>
Yishai explained that while Shas supports peace talks with
Syria, Shas legislators abstained in Monday's voting because Barak
had failed to provide them the details about the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He denied allegations that the party's abstention was connected
to an ongoing dispute with the government over the funding of its
debt-ridden religious school system. The Treasury and Education
Ministry have demanded that the party adopt a reform plan before
its school system could get funding.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef is
reportedly about to start a series of consultations with top
generals and politicians before he makes a religious ruling on the
peace talks with Syria. The spiritual leader is the ultimate
decision-maker of the party.
</P>
<P>
A decade ago Yosef ruled that territories must be ceded if that
means an end to any bloodshed, and this has been Shas' guiding
principle on peace talks. But some senior Shas politicians are
concerned now that the security of Israel could be compromised with
 a return to the border on the eve of the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
One of the most contentious issues between Israel and Syria is
Syria's demand that Israel withdraw its troops from the occupied
Golan Heights back to the pre-1967 war border, which would give
Syria control over the shore of the Sea of Galilee, the main source
 of fresh water for Israel.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Likud legislators criticized Weizman Wednesday for
what they called his intervention in politics while the public is
splitting over the issue of the Israeli-Syrian talks. They said the
 president should stay above party politics.
</P>
<P>
The sharp-mouthed Weizman, a strong advocate of Israeli-Arab
peace, has also angered the Jewish settlers in the Golan Heights
who oppose Barak's peace talks with Syria by expressing unequivocal
 support for the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
But Weizman denied he was taking a political stand, saying he
had always spoken out only in favor of what he thought was good for
 the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
