<HEADLINE> Boss of Leading S.African Soccer Club Shot to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Kaizer Chiefs Club, South
Africa's most popular soccer team, found its director and founder
Clarence Mlokoti was fatally shot during an attempted carjacking,
police in Soweto said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Two gunmen approached Mlokoti's car as it was stopped at a
house in Soweto Tuesday evening, said police Inspector Mbazima
Shiburi. They demanded the keys from Mlokoti's daughter, who had
been driving.
</P>
<P>
"On getting inside the car, they noticed there was somebody in
the back seat and shot him," said Putco Mafani, a team spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen fled, and Mlokoti, 69, later died in a hospital,
according to Shiburi.
</P>
<P>
Mlokoti founded the team and was a member of its board of
directors. Though based in Johannesburg, the Chiefs have a wide
national following and fans throughout the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mlokoti, a soft-spoken man, was responsible for introducing
sponsorship to black South African teams in the early 1970s,
inducing the corn meal company where he worked in marketing to
back the Chiefs, Mafani said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
