<HEADLINE> AL Welcomes Resumption of Syria-Israel Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Secretary General

Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Wednesday expressed welcome to the resumption
of the Syrian-Israeli peace talks after a freeze of nearly four
years.
</P>
<P>
The restart of the negotiations on the Syrian track will help
further promote the Middle East peace process, Abdel-Meguid told
reporters after meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to see a just and comprehensive peace on the Syrian,
Palestinian and Lebanese tracks," the chief of the Cairo-based
pan-Arab organization was quoted as saying by Egypt's Middle East
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Israel are to resume talks later Wednesday in
Washington. They will tackle the Israeli withdrawal from the Golan
Heights it captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War, security
arrangements, right to water resources and normalization of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said that he and Moussa also dealt with the latest
developments in the Arab world and exchanged views on the related
Arab League role in seeking ways of ironing out differences and
restoring solidarity of the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the latest developments of the situation in Sudan,
he expressed the league's support for the steps taken recently by
Sudanese President Omar Hassan al-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League has issued a statement backing the Sudanese
legitimacy. This is its absolute right. The league's stands are
clear, concerning the unity of Sudan and its territorial integrity.
We are keen on that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir declared Sunday night a three-month state of
emergency in all parts of the country and dissolved the Parliament
in what he said an effort to maintain national stability and
territorial integrity. 
</P>
