<HEADLINE> Manila Rules Out Transfer of Marcos Account </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential
Palace ruled out Wednesday the transfer of the dollar account of
the late President Ferdinand Marcos from the Philippine National
Bank (PNB) to the Central Bank of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said in a statement that
the deposit is bound to stay with the PNB under an escrow
agreement sealed between the parties as approved by the Swiss
Courts.
</P>
<P>
"Without the necessary judicial approval of a new escrow
agreement,the transfer of the dollar account from the PNB as
escrow agent to the Central Bank would be clearly illegal," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Barican also noted that the government retains a 30 percent
stake in the PNB which, like other commercial banks, operates
under the close supervision of the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The transfer of the dollar account of the Marcos family was
proposed by former Solicitor General Francisco Chavez, claiming
that the PNB is now in private hands.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Supreme Court earlier ruled that the money deposited
by the late president should be held in escrow until the
Philippine courts decide on the claims over the account of various
parties,including the government, the Marcos heirs, and the
victims martial law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
