<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops
have repelled Tamil rebels' repeated attempts since last Saturday
to take a strategically important causeway, a military spokesman
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, spokesman Brigadier Sunil
Tennekoon also said that 480 rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE)and 28 government soldiers were killed in the fighting
since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said government troops had 28 confrontations with the LTTE
rebels in the last four days near the Elephant Pass causeway,
about 280 km northeast of Colombo, which links the mainland and
the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
However, the LTTE said Monday that only 38 of their fighters
had died in the confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Independent confirmation of the casualties is impossible since
the government does not allow journalists to the war zone except
on military-conducted tours.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has intensified in recent weeks ahead of December 21
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Major General Lionel Balagalle said the timing of LTTE's
attacks appeared to be linked to the crucial presidential election
at which President Chandrika Kumaratunga is seeking reelection.
</P>
<P>
LTTE leader Prabhakaran said last month Kumaratunga's five-year
rule is a "curse" to Tamils, indicating his intention to try all
out to bring down the Kumaratunga government. 
</P>
