<HEADLINE> Macao Legislative Assembly Ends Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Sixth Legislative Assembly
of Macao held its last meeting here on Wednesday, indicating that
the legislature of Macao under Portuguese rule has ended its work.
</P>
<P>
The meeting passed a decision endorsing the Chinese versions of
18 laws and decrees adopted previously by the legislature. One
legislator put forward a motion requiring that the Portuguese
government in Lisbon pay the expenses of a Portuguese evening
party here on December 19. The motion was rejected by most
legislators. It has been decided that the cost of the evening
party in question will be borne by the current Portuguese Macao
government.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past three years, members of the Sixth Legislative
Assembly have spent a lot of time dealing with public issues,
thereby rendering their services to Macao and Macao residents with
their own style of work," said Anabela Ritchie, president of the
Legislative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
She said that the legislature had become a place to debate on
issues and safeguard the interests of citizens. She expressed the
belief that the Legislative Council of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) will assume a new outlook and
introduce new ideas.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Assembly of Macao came into being in August of
1976. Beginning from 1990, the legislature consisted of 23 members,
including eight elected directly by Macao voters, eight
recommended by social bodies and seven appointed by the governor
of Macao.
</P>
<P>
The First Legislative Council of the Macao SAR, which came into
being in September this year, has the same number of legislators.
The biggest difference is that seven of its members are appointed
by the chief executive of the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Macao SAR legislators are busy discussing bills
vital for a smooth operation of the Macao SAR government. The
bills are expected to be passed on the early morning of December
20 shortly after the establishment of the SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
