<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Busy Day for Farewell-Bidding Governor of Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- "We know how to build a bridge
of understanding for the future, we know how to link Portugal and
China, and we know how to cherish Macao," Portuguese Governor of
Macao Vasco Rocha Vieira said here today at the final meeting of
the Consultative Council of Macao, an advisory body to the Macao
government.
</P>
<P>
In a Chinese-Portuguese style meeting hall of the Praia Grande
Palace, the governor house, Vieira summed up his tenure over the
past eight-plus years.
</P>
<P>
"We have accomplished the objectives set in the (Sino-
Portuguese) Joint Declaration, built structural conditions for the
modernization of Macao and secured the basis of autonomy for the
Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Today is one of the busiest days for the governor who is
bidding farewell to Macao. In five days, he will return home to
Portugal as China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Macao.
</P>
<P>
As he spoke to the ten members of the Consultative Council and
the seven under-secretaries of the Macao Government, porters were
carrying Governor-Office-sealed cartons of books onto trucks from
the governor house.
</P>
<P>
There is a note of sadness as he recalled that many Portuguese
have left their marks and dreams in Macao and that some even met
the end of their lives here. However, the former general of the
Portuguese army said he will have many happy returns to Macao as a
tourist.
</P>
<P>
Lurdes Maria Da Luz, a staff member who has worked in the
Governor Office for nine years, said that most of the furnishings
in the governor house will remain the same as Vieira leaves the
palace.
</P>
<P>
"We will have a new leader, the first chief executive of the
Macao SAR Ho Hau Wah," she said.
</P>
<P>
Ho Hau Wah, the first head of the Macao SAR government, will be
sworn in on the early morning of December 20. Vieira is reported
to be leaving Macao hours later.
</P>
<P>
Vieira's departure will put a full stop to Western colonial
rule in Asia. However, he has shown personal affections for Macao.
In the Protocol and Public Relations Office of the governor house,
staff members were busying packaging gifts such as bronze plaques
bearing the insignia of the governor house. Most of the gifts are
to be presented to dignitaries from all walks of life in Macao and
friends of the governor.
</P>
<P>
Wendy Cordova Pun Weng U, who has worked with the office for
more than three years, said that staff members have been working
for 15-16 hours a day over the past week.
</P>
<P>
"We will remember these days," she said, "but we are also eager
to see the days ahead." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
