<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Proximity Talks on Cyprus to Be Held in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The second round of U.N.-
sponsored proximity talks on Cyprus is scheduled to be held in
Geneva from January 27 until February 6, 2000, the Cyprus News
Agency (CNA) reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks ended on Tuesday in New York under the
U.N. auspices to find a solution for the reunification of the
divided island. Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash were involved in the talks which
started on December 3.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
 invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in reaction
to a failed coup in Nicosia seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
CNA quoted "reliable sources" as saying that Clerides, leader of
 the Greek Cypriots, left New York satisfied after getting
assurance from the European Union (EU) Helsinki summit that the 15-
nation bloc will not make settlement of the Cyprus issue as a
precondition for Cyprus' accession talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
He expressed belief that the momentum created by the two-day EU
summit which ended last week will be translated into the
continuation of a new round of proximity talks next year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU membership in 1990 and started substantive
 accession negotiations with the EU in November 1998. It hopes to
be admitted as an EU member by January 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Economy Bounces Back in 3rd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia's economy bounced
back strongly in the third quarter, 1999, soaring 1.6 percent
seasonally adjusted, the strongest quarterly growth in over two
years, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ABS said that lifted economic growth for the year to
September to 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The strong recovery had been expected after the flat result in
the second quarter when the economy grew just 0.1 percent, revised
down from the original estimate of 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Once again the growth in the economy was driven by domestic
demand, with household consumption growing 1.3 percent seasonally
adjusted in the quarter, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
During the quarter, the country's exports rose 4.2 percent
seasonally adjusted, while imports rose 5.8 percent, meaning trade
was a negative factor in the economy, dragging back the already
high growth by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Property and business services was the strongest sector of the
economy, followed by retail trade, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture recorded a slight improvement, but not enough to
have an impact, while the construction and government sectors were
the only two to go backwards in the quarter, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
