<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Home Ownership Campaign Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Housing Developers
Association Malaysia (HDAM) Wednesday described the Home Ownership
Campaign in the country successful with sales exceeding the target.
</P>
<P>
Properties valued at 2.402 billion ringgit (632.105 million U.S.
dollars) were sold during the second Home Ownership Campaign held
between October 29 and December 7, exceeding the target of 2.0
billion ringgit (526.315 million U.S. dollars) that was intimated
to the Ministry of Finance and Bank Negara (State Bank) Malaysia
at the outset of the campaign, HDAM President Eddy Chen Lok Loi
said at a press conference Wednesday in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
The number of properties sold was 15,335 units, comprising
mainly medium-cost residential units against a total of 70,135
units of property offered for sale with a combined market value of
10.253 billion ringgit (2.698 billion U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
However, there are still leftovers of about 55,000 units which
are expected to be sold in six to nine months' time, he said,
adding that when these units were sold, the target sales of 125,
000 units under the Seventh Malaysia Plan (1996-2000) would be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
He urged developers not to increase the price of the unsold
properties offered during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
He said the HDAM was satisfied with the sales achieved during
the second campaign and was convinced the property market had
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia launched its first Home Ownership Campaign at the end
of last year aiming to prop up the demand for properties, during
which properties worth 1.6 billion ringgit (421 million U.S.
dollars) were sold.
</P>
<P>
When the first campaign was launched, the situation featured a
tight credit squeeze, tight monetary policies and slow sales in
view of the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
The second campaign was targeted to help further ease the
property market overhang under a new scenario, that is, an
economic recovery with a more flexible credit release, lower
interest rates and higher confidence in consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
The HDAM official said the campaigns were successful in
spurring up demand, contributing to more new property launches and
stability in property prices.
</P>
<P>
He said the association continued to urge caution in any new
project launches and suggested that developers carry out proper
market research to ensure that future project launches would be
salable and the oversupply situation experienced in 1997 and 1998
would not recur.
</P>
<P>
The HDAM announced that it had reactivated its Post Campaign
Monitoring Panel chaired by its deputy president Francis Ng Tian
Sang to deal with complaints and problems arising from the second
Home Ownership Campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
