<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Transportation Sector Y2K Ready: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's transportation
sector such as aviation, maritime and land transport would enter
into the new millennium with Y2K ready operations, Transport
Minister Ling Liong Sik said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
All sub-sectors have already taken and passed key remediation
effort including tests and contingency plans to confirm their
status as Y2K ready, he said at a press conference here..
</P>
<P>
He said that a team from the International Civil Aviation
Organization (ICAO) and International Air Transport Association(
IATA) was satisfied with the Y2K work achievement done by the
Department of Civil Aviation (DCA).
</P>
<P>
"MAS (Malaysia Airlines) and its aircraft, Malaysia Airports
Berhad (MAB) and the major ports in Malaysia are now operationally
Y2K ready," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said most of the ports' Y2K contingency plans also
include a period of "no operations" during the critical Y2K
rollover periods, both local and GMT time, ranging from two hours
to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Land transport such as STAR and PUTRA, both light rail
transport, as being new operators, are not much affected because
both started with all Y2K compliant related hardware, software and
equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K test done by KTM (railway operator) and its contractors
also indicate that KTM's commuter trains are Y2K ready and its
ticketing system even had already sold tickets into year 2000, he
said, adding the interstate trains are all diesel powered and will
not be affected by Y2K problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
