<HEADLINE> Australia to Provide Short-Term Loan to PNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia Wednesday agreed to
provide a 80-million-U.S. dollar short-term loan to Papua New
Guinea (PNG) to help with the nation's economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The loan, similar to the ones used to help prop up the Thai,
Indonesian and South Korean economies in 1997, follows an
agreement between PNG and the International Monetary Fund on an
economic restructuring package.
</P>
<P>
"This delivers on a commitment made by Prime Minister Howard
during his October 7-9 visit to Port Moresby," Australian Acting
Treasurer John Fahey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This short term facility will bolster PNG's reserves, allow
for a reduction in PNG government debt to the Bank of PNG and
contribute to a further strengthening of confidence in the PNG
economy," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fahey said Wednesday's announcement was in addition to the last
September decision to bring forward 20 million U.S. dollars in
budget support payments following the election of the Morauta
government. 
</P>
