<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scores of Tanzanian Infant Girls Die From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Scores of Tanzanian
infant girls have died from excessive bleeding since perpetrators
of female circumcision began to target toddlers, local media
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some tribes in the central Singida Region of Tanzania, which
are notorious for female circumcision, are using infants to dodge
the law and escape public persecution for performing the medieval
rituals, the independent Guardian newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"Since the rituals of circumcising women are illegal under the
Sexual Offences (Special Provisions) Act of 1998, some people are
now victimizing innocent babies because they can cut off their
external sex organs quietly and with less difficulty," the paper
quoted senior social welfare officer Zuhura Karya as saying.
</P>
<P>
She said a lot of infants could die from such experiences
because the rituals are performed with crude instruments such as
razor blades under unhygienic conditions.
</P>
<P>
There were many unreported cases in the region's remote
villages where girl babies bleed to death after being circumcised,
the officer said.
</P>
<P>
According to Karya, nearly half of the women giving birth in
Singida have been circumcised.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, different ethnic groups had different reasons for
circumcising their women, but the common reason among them is that
they believe an uncircumcised woman was dirty and likely to be
promiscuous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
