<HEADLINE> Japan's World Judo Champion Breaks a Pinky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Japan's four-time world judo
champion Ryoko Tamura has broken her little finger, a critical
injury, in a struggle against archrival Cuban Amarilis Savon.
</P>
<P>
Tamura broke her left hand's little finger when failing to
throw her opponent in the 48-kilogram bantamweight final at the
Fukuoka international women's judo championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Little fingers play a pivotal part in grabbing collars or
sleeves of opponents.
</P>
<P>
24-year-old Tamura won the close match on a 3-0 decision to
take her 10th straight bantamweight title in the contest.
</P>
<P>
"I wonder how I managed to fight Savon," Tamura said late
Tuesday after doctors determined that she needed about two months
to heal up the broken pinky.
</P>
<P>
She added that "Judging from X-rays, the muscles seem to be
partly torn also. I need to heal them up completely."
</P>
<P>
Tamura defeated Savon to runner-up in the last two world
championships. 
</P>
