<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Drops Duty-Free Privileges for Royal Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein has asked the government to stop waiving custom duties on
cars imported and licensed in the name of the Royal Court.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Prime Minister Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh dated Tuesday,
 Abdullah said all cars licensed under the Royal Court and owned by
 individuals should be subjected to custom duties.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure equality among people, said Abdullah,
necessary measures must be taken to prevent the registration of any
 vehicle for the duty-free benefit for any person or institution
under the name of the Royal Court.
</P>
<P>
The move has been hailed by Jordanian officials as a step in the
 right direction to curb the losses of much-needed fund to the
state treasury.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that some 3,000 duty-free cars are
roaming the Jordanian roads though independent estimates put the
figure at 10,000, most of them are luxurious cars owned by former
officials and tribal leaders.
</P>
<P>
Car dealers said the average duties for the top-class high
petrol-consuming cars ran at about 10,000 Jordanian dinars (14,000
U.S. dollars), meaning the state treasury may lose up to 100
million dinars (140 million dollars) due to inappropriate duty
waivers.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom can not manufacture cars and most of the cars in use
 are imported from Germany, the United States, Japan, France and
South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technical Arrangement About Ethio-Eritrean War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi has reiterated that the United States proposed
technical arrangement to solve Ethio-Eritrean conflict is not
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
In a briefing to African ambassadors Tuesday, Meles said
"Ethiopia has bent backwards with the U.S./Rwanda proposals and
has bent more with the framework agreement, bending any further
would break our back and we are not ready to do that."
</P>
<P>
Meles criticized the technical arrangement for its failure to
guarantee the fundamental principle of international law.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the high price that Ethiopia paid to
achieve the return to the status quo anti is primarily not for
land but is for principle.
</P>
<P>
Any head of state cannot force Ethiopia to change the
principle, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
Meles said Ethiopia will remain committed to the letter and
spirit of the two basic documents -- the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) proposed pace package and the modalities for its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the technical arrangement could be worked out
in such a way as to be consistent with the two fundamental
documents and the principles contained therein." he said.
</P>
<P>
Meles said Ethiopia appreciated the stand taken by African
countries which, he said, were consistent with the OAU Charter,
international laws and principles governing inter-state relations.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have been at war since May 1998, since
which tens of thousands people have been killed and injured in the
battles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
