<HEADLINE> Radical Ethnic Group Behind Attack on Nigeria's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Lagos State Police
said on Tuesday that eight suspects arrested so far in connection
with the attack upon the state's Governor Ahmed Tinubu are
members of the Oodua People's Congress (OPC), which was behind
last month's Lagos ethnic conflict in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
The New Nigerian newspaper Wednesday quoted Mike Okiro, the
state's police chief, as saying that one of those arrested is a
top OPC member, a radical Yoruba ethnic group, which fought with
the immigrant Ijaws in an ethnic clash last month, which killed
about 100 people in Lagos, Nigeria's biggest city.
</P>
<P>
The attack upon the governor occurred on Sunday afternoon in an
area near the governor's official residency, when the governor's
convoy was blocked by seven commercial vehicles occupied by about
20 attackers.
</P>
<P>
Describing the experience as a "frightening one", Governor
Tinubu said Monday that a bullet penetrated his car and several
of this security men were badly injured during the incident.
</P>
<P>
In fighting back, the governor's security men killed four
attackers and arrested five at the scene. The state's police said
they were investigating on the motives behind the attack.
</P>
<P>
Following the attack, Tinubu and the state's legislature Monday
renewed their calls for a state controlled police force, which
the federal government did not approve several month ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
