<HEADLINE> Mainland Police to Handle Applications for HK Jobs at Beginning of 2000 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Mainlanders looking for jobs
in Hong Kong can expect their applications to be reviewed starting
January 1, 2000, the Ministry of Public Security announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
A senior police officer from the ministry's Exit and Entry
Administration said that the move is aimed to help implement the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)'s program of
introducing more high-caliber talent into the region so as to
improve its competitive edge in the global market.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Hong Kong-registered companies can submit
application forms to the SAR government for the employment of
mainland talent. The SAR government will sign and issue entry
permits to those who are hired, as well as to their spouses and
children under age 21.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the Exit and Entry Administration has
formulated a regulation on the approval of mainlanders seeking job
opportunities in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, the applicants should have the
permits issued by the SAR's entry department, and job seekers
should get the approval from their mainland employers before they
can submit application forms to their local public security
bureaus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
