<HEADLINE> 160,000 Tanzanians in Need of Emergency Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 160,000
people in the central Singida Region of Tanzania are in need of
emergency food aid as a prolonged dry spell hit half of the
villages in this semi-arid area.
</P>
<P>
The independent Guardian newspaper Wednesday quoted Acting
Singida Regional Commissioner Martin Mgongolwa as saying that more
than 156,000 people in the region need emergency food aid from
this month to next April.
</P>
<P>
"This year's survey of the food situation in Singida shows that
there's an acute shortage of 9,500 tons of food," the commissioner
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the majority of those in need of food aid in the region
are people who do not have food reserves, livestock or employment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"An accumulation of adverse weather effects from last year to
this year resulted in the food deficit in many parts of the
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Regional Commissioner's Office has intervened in
the alarming food situation by encouraging farmers to cultivate
drought resistant crops.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is expected to face a shortage of 600,000 tons of food
next year due to bad weather in various parts of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
