<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, U.S. -- The U.S. Government Tuesday said that it will
work hard to help African nations with sustainable development,
which means to tap the potential of its rich energy resources
while paying close attention to environmental protection on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a key-note speech at the plenary session of the
three-day U.S.-Africa Energy Ministers Conference, which kicked
off here on Monday evening, Bill Richardson, the U.S. secretary of
energy, said that, "Though we gather from different points on the
globe, we share a commitment to Africa, to its sustainable energy
development, its integration into the world marketplace, and its
overall prosperity." "For Africa, sustainable energy development
would enhance prosperity, diminish poverty and liberate resources
for essentials such as health services," he said. (US-Africa-
Energy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- An earthquake measuring 4.5 on the Richter scale
jolted the Mexican capital and the southern state of Oaxaca
Tuesday, but no damage was reported.
</P>
<P>
The National Seismological Service reported that the moderate
quake hit the two areas at 01:11 am (local time) and was centered
in the continental mass between the adjoining states of Guerrro
and Oaxaca, both along the Pacific Ocean. Many residents rushed
out of their homes for fear of collapse in the Pinotepa de Don
Luis municipality in Oaxaca, where the quake was felt more
strongly, local authorities said. (Mexico-Quake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Dismissed Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile
appeared Tuesday to have accepted his ouster by President Emil
Constantinescu, saying that he would return to the senate "in the
national interest."
</P>
<P>
Vasile said late Tuesday that he has decided to return to the
senate "to be an ordinary senator" and that he does not want to
see the crisis last long. Vasile, who was sacked by the president
early Tuesday after major parties in the ruling coalition withdrew
support for him, said he would not go to the constitutional court
over the justification of his dismissal, but adding that he would
not announce his resignation either. (Romania-PM-Senator)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh arrived in Washington on Tuesday for
the resumption of mideast peace talks that broke off nearly four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the Dulles International Airport outside the
Washington D.C., Shareh told reporters that his country was
serious about peace and hoped Israel would reciprocate. "We are
looking forward to a productive meeting. We hope we can pave the
way for a peace agreement," Shareh said. "We are serious about
reaching a result. We hope that the Israeli side will reciprocate
our desire for peace." Barak arrived at Andrews Air Force base on
the other side of Washington about ten minutes later and drove off
to Washington without speaking to reporters. (US-Israel-Syria)
</P>
