<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Complete Bank Recapitalization by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
would complete its banking reorganization and recapitalization
program of all of state banks by June 2000, a senior minister said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to completing the reorganization and
recapitalization of all of the state banks by June 2000 and at the
same time we plan to complete the reorganization and consolidation
of the banks taken-over by government (BTO) and the liquidated
banks by September of next year," Coordinating Minister for
Economy, Finance and Industry Kwik Kian Gie said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would move forward with a vigorous
program to privatize the banking system.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to begin the privatization process by selling part
of the government stake in Bank Central Asia (BCA) by February
2000," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
BCA is the country's largest private bank. The bank now has
been under control of government as it failed to meet the capital
adequate ratio (CAR) requirements of 4 percent as stipulated by
the new law of banking.
</P>
<P>
The government would then proceed with majority divestment of
key state banks and BTO banks, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement with the International Monetary Fund, the
Indonesian government closed 16 commercial banks found unhealthy
in November 1997. On April 4 last year, the government froze the
operation of seven private banks and put seven others under the
supervision of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency. Four
month later, the government froze the operation of three banks and
took over the ownership of four other banks.
</P>
<P>
In March 1999, government had closed down 38 private banks
while putting seven others under government management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Calls for U.N. Policy to Iron out Differences with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) has called
on the United Nations Security Council to work out a new policy on
the U.N.-Iraqi relations in a bid to iron out differences and
execute the relevant resolutions, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The AL said in a statement issued by its secretariat general on
Tuesday that it has been closely following up the consultations
underway in the U.N. Security Council on formulating new ways of
dealing with the Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
The 22-nation pan-Arab organization demanded the council to make
 positive reaction to Iraq's readiness to cooperate with the U.N.
if a proper policy is worked out by the world organization.
</P>
<P>
"This new policy should give Baghdad hope that there is light at
 the end of the tunnel," the AL statement said, quoted by the
paper.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is considering vote on a draft
resolution proposed by Britain on suspension of international trade
 sanctions on Iraq after it is certified to have cooperated with
the U.N. under a new regime for weapons verification in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has rejected the British proposal, insisting that it has
fully carried out its commitments and the U.N. Security Council
should lift the sanctions imposed after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The AL expressed appreciation for the endeavors aimed at easing
the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council approved last Friday a six-month
extension to the humanitarian oil-for-food program in Iraq after
weeks of haggling about the future policy toward Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The program offers an exception to the crippling U.N. economic
sanctions. It allows Iraq to export 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth
of oil in six months to buy food and medicine for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
