<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Won't Ask Debt Butchering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 15, (Xinhua) -- Indonesia would not ask hair
cut but debt rescheduling to donor countries or international
institutions, a senior official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will just ask for a rescheduling of our debt, but not hair
cut. We will reduce the total of our debt with reducing the number
of
financial aids (from donor countries), not asking hair cut,"
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry Kwik Kian
Gie told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the country would not ask debt butchering as such a
move would just endanger the Indonesian economy as the
international donors would no longer give their financial
assistance.
</P>
<P>
"If we asked for hair cut, we will be isolated by international
community. And cash inflow into Indonesia will be halted and the
people of Indonesia will undergo an extraordinary torment," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries grouped in the Consultative Group for Indonesia
(CGI) is expected to hold its first meeting in Jakarta on February
1-2, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Asked how much financial aid would be proposed to the donors,
Kwik Kian Gie refused to comment, saying it has still been under
calculation.
</P>
<P>
"But We will be proud if the commitment (of financial aid) from
CGI would be smaller than the previous commitment," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement Signed on Nuclear Reactor Construction in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Korean Peninsula Energy
Development Organization (KEDO) and the Korea Electric Power Corp.
(KEPCO) signed an agreement Wednesday here for the construction of
two light-water reactors in the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by KEDO Executive Director Desaiz
Anderson and KEPCO President Choi Soo-byong, with more than 80
celebrities, including the ambassadors of the 12 KEDO member
states, attending the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, comprised of 38 articles and 22 appendices,
stipulates the duties of the KEPCO, KEDO and the DPRK for the
construction of the two reactors.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, KEPCO will build the two light-water
reactors, install and manage fundamental facilities, while KEDO is
responsible for supplying a work site, communication facilities
and securing workers' safety.
</P>
<P>
The two light-water reactors with a capacity of 1,000 megawatts
each will be built in Kumho, an eastern coastal area of the DPRK's
Hamyong Province, at a cost of 4.6 billion U.S. dollars, of which
South Korea will provide 32.2 billion, Japan 10 billion and the
United States the rest.
</P>
<P>
It will take eight and nine years to complete the construction
of the two reactors respectively.
</P>
<P>
Some 220 South Korean engineers from KEPCO, Hyundai, Daewoo and
Korea Heavy Industries have finished preliminary projects such as
ground-leveling and infrastructure in Kumho.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the DPRK signed an agreement in Geneva in
October 1994 to build the reactors in return for Pyongyang's
abandonment of its suspected nuclear development.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Geneva agreement, the construction of
the reactors would be completed and put into operation in 2003.
However, the deadline has to be postponed to 2007 or 2008.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang has complained about the slow pace of the
construction, even threatening to scrap the 1994 agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
