<HEADLINE> FIFA Tries to Stop Black Market Sales for 2002 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- World football governing
body FIFA is working on a cohesive ticketing strategy for the 2002
World Cup to try to stop black market sales and give genuine fans
more protection.
</P>
<P>
Peter Velappan, FIFA 2002 World Cup coordination director, said
it was
finalising the price of tickets and would work out a schedule for
orders from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a statement, Velappan, who is also the Asian
Football Confederation secretary, said that Japan had asked for an
allocation for 1.5 million tickets.
</P>
<P>
Velappan, who visited the two host countries -- Japan and South
Korea ealier this month with FIFA general secretary Michel Zen
Ruffinen, noted that they were satisfied with progress in building
stadiums.
</P>
<P>
Velappan said FIFA would organise friendly international
matches in each of the stadiums to test the infrastructure,
manpower organisation, logistics and the movement of teams between
the two countries. 
</P>
