<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Calm and Orderly Before Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Rita Santos arrives at her
office at 9:00 am, the time to start work at government offices in
Macao. For Rita Santos, deputy director of Macao Municipal Council,
and other public servants here, business as usual marks their
attitude and state of mind as they discharge their different
duties, though Macao's return to China on December 20 lies only
five days ahead.
</P>
<P>
Rita Santos, also chairman of the Public Servants Association
of Macao, says that all the 6,680 members of the association are
expected to stay in Macao after the handover.
</P>
<P>
"We want to work for the Macao Special Administrative Region (
MSAR) Government," she said, "to carry out the policies of 'one
country, two systems' and 'Macao people administering Macao'."
</P>
<P>
There are at present 18,000 public servants in Macao, who have
generally remained calm, though certain changes in the framework
of the government are expected to take place after December 20.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao,
which was signed 12 years ago, states that, for 50 years after the
handover, Macao's previous social and economic system and way of
life will remain unchanged and that Macao's existing laws will
remain basically unchanged. The commitment is enshrined in the
Basic Law of the MSAR enacted by the National People's Congress
six years later.
</P>
<P>
Macao has remained calm and stable for the past 12 years, the
transitional period for the region before it reverts to Chinese
rule.
</P>
<P>
At the same time when the Portuguese Macao Government and
Legislative Assembly have remained operational, the MSAR
Government and Legislative Council have been established. All
previous public servants, lawmakers and judges in Macao who are
eligible in accordance with the Basic Law may hold their positions
if they so wish. All previous laws in Macao that do not contravene
the Basic Law will become laws of the MSAR and remain effective in
post-handover Macao.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the smooth transition, local residents have kept
their lifestyle unaffected for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, people flock to parks to do exercises, or go
shopping at food markets. In the evening, casinos are filled with
people seeking instant riches. U Kin Lung, a young student
returning home from his Australian university for holidays, says
what has impressed him most is that everything is orderly in Macao
and nothing has changed in the way of life.
</P>
<P>
Local businessmen do not want to miss opportunities created by
Macao's handover. Victor Leung, a local entrepreneur, says he
plans to expand his garment factory by moving it to Coloane Island.
</P>
<P>
In the Macau Polytechnic Institute, students stay late into the
night in lecture rooms. Many young people, including Macanese, or
locally-born Portuguese, are busy learning Chinese in the hope of
finding better jobs in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
