<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reclamation No Longer Disturbs Birds' Paradise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- For half a century, hundreds of
thousands of demobilized soldiers and urban youngsters have worked
to reclaim wasteland in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province,
but their crusade has come to an end.
</P>
<P>
The central government has made the decision to stop reclaiming
the wasteland, known as the "Great Northern Wildness," to save an
ever-shrinking habitat for water birds.
</P>
<P>
The wilderness, bordering Russia, annually turns out 6.5
million tons of grain, an amount which is able to feed the
citizens of Hong Kong and Macao for four years. China started to
send people to the fertile but cold region five decades ago to
solve its food problem.
</P>
<P>
In the wilderness, one of the three major black soil belts in
the world, China cultivated two million hectares of farmland with
agricultural machinery -- more than anywhere else in the country --
making it a giant grain base.
</P>
<P>
As the reclamation area becomes larger and larger, the size of
wetlands there has shrunk by 60 percent, forcing red-crowned
cranes, white storks and other water fowl on the verge of
extinction to fly elsewhere to survive.
</P>
<P>
With a network of rivers, swamps and dense forests, the
wetlands have been put on an international wetlands protection
list.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, wildlife experts have appealed to the
government to stop encroaching on the Great Northern Wilderness.
Liu Xingtu, deputy director of the Wetlands Research Center of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, warned that "the wetlands will
disappear in a dozen years if no effective measures are taken."
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Chinese government finally announced it would
stop further reclaiming the Great Northern Wilderness and instead
set up nature reserves and plant trees to improve the local
ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhicai, deputy director of the Agricultural Reclamation
Bureau under the Ministry of Agriculture, said that although
further reclamation has been stopped, the status of the Great
Northern Wilderness as a major grain base remains unaffected.
</P>
<P>
Wang explained that with the help of science and technology,
the grain output of the wilderness will not drop; in fact, the
already reclaimed area will provide more and better grain for
China.
</P>
<P>
Shen Liguo, an official in charge of the Great Northern
Wilderness reclamation, said that emphasis will be placed on the
improvement of the species of agricultural crops and their unit
yield.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are being made to reform over one million hectares of
low- and medium-yield farmland, a move which is meant to attain an
additional 2.5 million tons of grain annually, he added.
</P>
<P>
Shen put this year's grain output in the Great Northern
Wilderness at a record high of nine million tons. "But not a
single granule of grain came from any new plots of land," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
