<HEADLINE> Macao SAR Passport Recognized Internationally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The passport of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR), which is to be established
on December 20, has won recognition by a number of countries
including the United States, Myanmar, Japan, France and Canada,
since samples of the MSAR passport and travel document were
announced last August.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Korea and some other countries have recently
announced their recognition of the MSAR passport, and some
countries are known to consider granting visa-free treatment to
bearers of the MSAR passport, according to Macao Identification
Services.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, however, has not yet made an official statement about
its recognition of the MSAR passport, although it once expressed
its intention to be the first country to grant visa-free treatment
to holders of the passport.
</P>
<P>
Portugal's lukewarm response has the public here concerned and
has also brought about inconveniences to MSAR passport holders,
some of whom will travel to Portugal and western Europe during
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Last week, relevant governmental departments of Hong Kong and
Macao announced entry arrangements for Hong Kong and Macao
residents traveling between the two regions after Macao's return
to China on December 20.
</P>
<P>
The MSAR government will issue a Hong Kong travel permit for
Macao residents, who are not to use the MSAR passport as a travel
document for Hong Kong, according to Macao Identification Services.
</P>
<P>
Of late, Macao Identification Services receives some 300 to 400
MSAR passport applicants every day, and nearly 90 percent of
applicants having made an appointment in advance have also been to
offices of the Services to go through application procedures,
according to the Services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
