<HEADLINE> Expansion Of Wildlife Rescue Center In E. China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Preparations are now complete
for an expansion project at a state-level wildlife rescue center
at Mount Fenghuang in the southern part of east China's Anhui
Province.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is estimated to cost some 10 million yuan (1.
2 million US dollars), will take three years, and will greatly
improve rescue, nursing, educational, and research facilities at
the center.
</P>
<P>
Three breeding bases for rare wildlife will be built, along
with a hall to house many wild animals living in the province, a
center capable of accommodating over 50 amphibious reptiles, a
veterinary hospital, and a center for education.
</P>
<P>
The wildlife rescue center opened in 1998 after a two-year
first phase of construction, and so far has taken in more than 300
injured wild animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Hosts More Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Overseas tourists
contributed 822.2 million US dollars in foreign currency to the
metropolitan business center in south China's Guangdong Province
in the first three quarters of this year, up 6.3 percent on a
yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
The number of overseas tourists hosted by the city reached 2.3
million in the nine-month period, 60 percent of which were from
Hong Kong and Macao, according to latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
In total, the city had 41.3 million domestic and overseas
tourists, with the combined tourism revenues reaching 23.46
billion yuan (2.83 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has been actively creating a sound tourist
environment and developing attractive tourist itineraries and
products this year, local tourism authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from some southeast Asian countries,
which suffered from a financial crisis in 1998, has increased
rapidly, they said.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from Europe and America increased 11.7
percent in the nine-month period; that of domestic tourists, up
more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The tourist boom brought a 10.9 and 7.9 percent year-on-year
increase in the turnover of the city's catering industry and the
total retail sales volume, respectively, statistics show.
</P>
</TEXT>
