<HEADLINE> Deputy PM to Lead Lebanon's Team for Talks with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 15 (Xinhua) -- In a surprise announcement,
Lebanese Deputy Prime Minister and Interior Minister Michel Murr
has disclosed that he would head Lebanon's team for peace
negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"I was asked to head the team because I'm entitled to be the
acting foreign minister,"Murr was quoted by the Daily Star
newspaper as saying on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A source close to Prime Minister Salim Hoss said that Hoss
decided not to lead the team himself "because his main job is the
premiership and because the Lebanese-Israeli talks will proceed in
most stages at the level of diplomats."
</P>
<P>
The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told the paper
that "the government doesn't expect Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to head his country's delegations to the talks with Lebanon.
Therefore, there is no need for Hoss to head Lebanon's team in the
talks."
</P>
<P>
The remarks came as Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa was
 to meet in Washington Wednesday with Barak for landmark
negotiations aimed at ending a half-century of hostilities between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Murr said the date for the resumption of the Lebanese-Israeli
talks has not been set but will come soon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-styled security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with declared aim to stop cross-border attacks by Lebanese
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has been demanding an unconditional Israeli withdrawal
from its territory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
