<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Drops by Nine Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 15 (Xinhua)-- Zimbabwe's year-on-year rate of
inflation in November took a surprising turn, dropping by 9.2
percent to 61. 2 percent from a record 70.4 percent, the country's
Central Statistical office said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Food inflation lost 17 percentage points over the October rate
of 86.4 percent to 69.4 percent while non-food inflation stood at
55.6 percent, shedding 4.1 percent from the October rate of 59.7
percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The decrease in inflation to 61.2 percent from 70.4 percent in
October, 1999 is largely explained by the rapid increase in
November's month-on month inflation last year by nine percent
compared with 3.1 percent this year during the same period," the
office said.
</P>
<P>
According to economic analyst Andy Hodges, the country's
inflation seems to have peaked and could start to decline in the
coming year if all unforeseeable factors are discounted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
