<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maps of Japanese Invasion Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The four maps found in the
archives of a coal mine in Luoyang City of Henan Province, central
China, have been confirmed as being military maps used by Japanese
aggressors when they occupied the area in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The maps, all classified as "top military confidential," were
found as workers were clearing up documents in the old Longmen
Mine archive.
</P>
<P>
According to Liang Yuting, head of the archive, the four maps
show details of two major Henan Province cities, Kaifeng and
Luoyang, including rivers and mountains, and streets, buildings
and village routes.
</P>
<P>
The four maps were apparently drawn in the early 1930s, Liang
said, adding that this shows that the Japanese imperialists had
planned aggression against China years before 1937, when the War
of Resistance Against Japan began.
</P>
<P>
When they eventually invaded Luoyang in 1944, the Japanese
first occupied the strategic site of the Longmen Mine and looted
the coal resources there. The maps are believed to have been left
by the Japanese invaders when they retreated prior to their
surrender in 1945, he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
