<HEADLINE> UAE to Draft Building Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Public Works
and Housing in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) is working on framing
 a federal building law, which is to be the key to sustaining
future growth in the country's construction sector.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry has been apprised of the long-standing demand of
the building sector for a federal law in this field, and steps have
 been taken to come up with a solution, according to senior
industry sources.
</P>
<P>
Currently only the emirate of Dubai has laws related to
construction and there is an increasing need for a UAE-wide
implementation of a building code, said Ahmed Saif Belhasa,
chairman of UAE Contractors Association and president of the World
Organization of Building Officials, quoted by the Gulf News daily
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The UAE's construction sector is worth 20 billion dirhams (about
 5.46 billion U.S. dollars) a year, and the absence of a federal
law is a major problem for the industry now, Belhasa said.
</P>
<P>
"Things are cooking, though we are not sure as to when we can
expect definite results on the building law," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sector is pushing for the creation of an
authoritative body, which will enforce the regulations once they
are passed into law, Belhasa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
