<HEADLINE> China Hosts Seminar on Forestry Development, Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- An international seminar
started here today to discuss the growth and fund raising issues
facing China's forestry industry under the market economy and
outline the development strategy for the future.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar is co-sponsored by the China Development
Bank (CDB), the State Administration of Forestry (SAF) and the
World Bank (WB).
</P>
<P>
Chen Yuan, president of CDB, said that as a policy bank, CDB
provides loans to support the country's key projects in
infrastructure, basic and pillar industries. Its total amount of
loans has hit more than 600 billion yuan (72 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said that previously, CDB's funds in forestry were mainly
used in exploiting natural forests. But in the coming years, the
bank will focus on building large and fast-growing forest
conservation projects and protecting natural forests, in line with
the country's "Natural Forest Projects in Selected Areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, one of the earliest to back China's forestry
industry, has injected 800 million U.S. dollars into six large
forestry projects over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Juergen Voegele, acting head of the WB residential office in
Beijing, said that WB is willing to "establish a new partnership"
with China to help solve new problems that emerge in the forestry
industry's transformation period.
</P>
<P>
He said that WB will do its utmost to provide China with needed
funds, technological assistance and related consultation services.
</P>
<P>
China's forestry industry has made considerable achievements in
the past two decades since the opening-up policy began. Its
forestation coverage ratio rose from 12 percent to the current 13.
92 percent. The figure is expected to reach 18.2 percent in 2005,
and 19 percent in 2010, according to an official with the SAF.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, said SAF's Director Wang Zhibao, China has
worked out its 21st-century-oriented development strategy that
focuses on promoting local development, readjusting the economic
structure and pushing forward modern forestry construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
