<HEADLINE> Kenyan Government Clears Toll Booths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
ordered to remove all toll stations imposed by local authorities
in the east African country in a bid to improve the transport.
</P>
<P>
Toll stations along some sections of the roads were removed
just following the decree issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Motorists were forced to pay 40 shillings (about 0.5 U.S.
dollar) to 200 shillings (around 2.7 dollars) per trip, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some private bus-owners in Kenya's Coast Province appreciated
the move by the government for reducing their financial burdens.
</P>
<P>
In the southwest province of Nyanza, a strike planned by over
2,000 bus- owners was averted after the contentious toll sites
were cleared.  
</P>
