<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Gives Ultimatum to Probe Helicopters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's parliamentary
committee on defense and internal affairs has given State
Minister for Defense Steven Kavuma a three-month ultimatum to give
a report on the helicopters rejected by the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Tuesday at the committee's meeting also
attended by the ministry's Permanent Secretary Ben Mbonye, the New
Vision daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chris Mudoola, who chaired the meeting, was quoted as saying
there were some officials involved in bribery and inflating the
price of the helicopters but the committee had not yet received a
report on this. He advised that the committee institute a
commission of inquiry into the matter.
</P>
<P>
In February 1997, the Ministry of Defense ordered for four
overhauled helicopters through a British Virginia-registered
company, Consolidated Sales Corporation, at a cost of 12 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministry paid a deposit of 6.5 million dollars to the
supplier but the first group of two choppers were rejected because
they were not overhauled as required.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports saying that some senior military
officers were involved in the helicopter scandal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
