<HEADLINE> BSE Sounds Alarm Against 23 Firms in IT Clothing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bombay Stock Exchange (
BSE) has raised alarm against 23 companies that have changed their
names to suggest a shift in focus to software related activities
from their core business (mostly financial activities) in the
current year.
</P>
<P>
The list, published in "The Economic Times" Wednesday, is in
addition to the 20 companies that were announced on January 27,
1998.
</P>
<P>
"The names of the companies are being announced to warn
investors against such companies," a BSE spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The move has been taken in the wake of increasing volumes and
prices in information technology (IT) and software stocks in
general,he said.
</P>
<P>
The exchange has issued specific instructions to members to
take necessary precaution while placing orders in the Scripps with
an infotech tag.
</P>
<P>
They have been also asked to verify their fundamentals before
taking any investment decision.
</P>
<P>
The move has been taken to check excess volatility, which has
already led to multi-fold rise in the stock prices.
</P>
<P>
For instance, After Infosys, which quoted at 43 rupees (1 U.S.
dollar) on January 1, 1999, is currently ruling at 1,823 rupees (
42.40 dollars) on the BSE appreciating over 42 times in less than
a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
