<HEADLINE> East China Province Gives Priority to Waterfront Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province,
which ranks second in the country in terms of GDP, has decided to
give priority to the development of industries along the country's
longest river, the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the provincial government say the decision aims to
turn the region into a major industrial center of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, cities along the 433-km-long Jiangsu
section of the Yangtze will focus on raw and processed materials,
and various new and high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment and export-oriented processing are
encouraged, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
There are eight cities along the Yangtze in Jiangsu, and in
1998 they as a whole generated 539 billion yuan in GDP, accounting
for 75 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the waterfront cities, including Nanjing, the
provincial capital, Zhenjiang and Nantong, have an improved
business environment.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, the province has built 73 large berths,
including eight container berths, in these cities. And industries
of iron and steel, chemicals, building materials, papermaking, and
ship repairing have been formed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
