<HEADLINE> Lakers Whitewashes Clippers 95-68 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Los Angeles Clippers
set NBA records Tuesday night by scoring only 19 points in the
first half and three in the second quarter of a 95-68 loss to the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
The previous record for fewest points in a half since the 24-
second shot clock went into effect was 20 by the New Orleans Jazz
at Seattle on January 4, 1975.
</P>
<P>
The previous lowest-scoring second quarter was five points by
both Utah in 1981 and the Knicks last season.
</P>
<P>
Shaquille O'Neal collected 21 points and 19 rebounds while
playing just 29 minutes. Kobe Bryant had 18 points and Glen Rice
totalled 17.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, Utah Jazz ousted Washington 101-80. Karl Malone
scored 34 points to help Utah Jazz stretch their winning streak to
six.
</P>
<P>
All five Utah starters scored in double figures.
</P>
<P>
in Atlanta, Dikembe Mutombo shot 11-for-11 and had 27 points
and 29 rebounds as Atlanta edged Minnesota 105-94.
</P>
<P>
Mutombo's rebound total was the highest in the NBA since Dennis
Rodman grabbed 29 for Chicago against Atlanta on December 27, 1997.
It was two shy of Mutombo's career-high of 31 and offset an
outstanding night by Kevin Garnett.
</P>
<P>
Garnett had the sixth triple-double of the NBA season with 22
points, 15 rebounds and 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
Cleveland defeated Boston 115-88 in Cleveland. Bob Sura
totalled 22 points and 10 assists and Lamond Murray collected 20
points as Cleveland sent Boston to its seventh straight road loss.
</P>
<P>
Shawn Kemp played just 16 minutes and scored 16 points. Mark
Bryant came off the bench and added 12 points for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
In Toronto, Raptors beat Indiana Pacers 105-97. Vince Carter
had 24 points and Antonio Davis scored 16 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
After Indiana pulled within one point with 4:55 remaining, the
Raptors went on a 10-2 run as Charles Oakley had a tip-in and an
assist to Tracy McGrady for an alley-oop dunk.
</P>
<P>
McGrady tied his season-high with 21 points. Oakley also had 11
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
In Houston, Patrick Ewing scored 20 points, including 14 in the
first quarter as the New York Knicks outclassed Houston Rockets
101-90.
</P>
<P>
Allan Houston also scored 20, including 10 in the third period.
</P>
<P>
In Dallas, Tim Duncan totalled 29 points and 12 rebounds as the
San Antonio Spurs won from Dallas Mavericks 111-93.
</P>
<P>
Avery Johnson added 16 points and David Robinson had 10 points
and nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Cedric Ceballos' 27 points and 10 rebounds paced the Mavericks,
losers of four of their last five games.
</P>
<P>
Phoenis Suns defeated Detroit Pistons 114-104 in Phoenix. Scott
Skiles' debut as head coach of the Suns was a success Tuesday
night behind Jason Kidd's 18 points, 11 assists and nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Rex Chapman scored a season-high 22 for the Suns. Oliver Miller
had 17 and Tom Gugliotta 16 as seven Phoenix players scored in
double figures.
</P>
<P>
In Seattle, Gary Payton scored 25 points in the first three
quarters before taking a seat on the bench for the rest of the
night as the Seattle SuperSonics overwhelmed Denver 109-84.
</P>
<P>
In Oakland, California, Warriors Golden States defeated Miami
Heat 102-97. Chris Mills totalled 23 points and John Starks scored
21 as the Warriors won their third straight after an 11-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
Alonzo Mourning collected 26 points to lead Miami, which
entered the game with the best record in the Eastern Conference.
Voshon Lenard scored 18 points and P.J. Brown added 16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
