<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclone John Hits Western Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The most powerful cyclone
ever recorded in Australia, with winds of up to 300 kph, smashed
into Western Australia's north coast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyclone John thundered over the coast near the tiny community
of Whim Creek, but emergency services believe bigger coastal towns
such as Karratha would escape its full fury.
</P>
<P>
John is a top-rating category five cyclone and Bureau of
Meteorology of Australia cyclone forecaster Brian Bowase said it
was "unequivocally the most powerful ever recorded in Australia.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking at winds of almost 300 km an hour and quite
frankly that's bloody unbelievable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bowase said John was stronger than both cyclone Vance, which
destroyed much of Exmouth earlier this year, and cyclone Tracy
that devastated Darwin in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclone Ilsa Follows John in Western Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bureau of Meteorology of
Australia warned on Wednesday that a second tropical cyclone is
following in the wake of cyclone John and may cross Western
Australia's Pilbara coast on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cyclone forecaster Brian Bowase said cyclone Ilsa had been
classified category one but was expected to be upgraded as it
approached the coast between Broome and Exmouth.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know how strong it's going to get but we're
continuing to monitor it," Bowase said.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking at strong gales as it crosses the coast,
probably some time tomorrow, but the main thing could be the heavy
rainfall coming on top of the rains brought by (cyclone) John."
</P>
<P>
He said it was not uncommon for one cyclone to follow another,
and the two were not believed to be linked.
</P>
<P>
It was not possible to say exactly where cyclone Ilsa would hit.
</P>
<P>
Cyclone John, which passed over the tiny coastal community of
Whim Creek Wednesday morning, is the strongest cyclone ever
recorded in Australia with wind speeds of up to 300kph.
</P>
<P>
It has been downgraded to a category four cyclone, and wind
speeds of 260kph are expected in nearby Roebourne and Port Sampson.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rainfall and flooding are expected across the Pilbara
coast Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
