<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Major Thai Cabinet Members under Fire in Censure Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Three major cabinet members of
the Thai government are under fire as the no-confidence debate
against the ruling coalition kicked off Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition New Aspiration Party targeted its fire
against Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmannahaeminda and Deputy Prime Minister and Interior Minister
Sanan Kachornprasart.
</P>
<P>
Chuan faces accusation of being a "puppet" of foreign interests,
after implementing austere International Monetary Fund conditions
in exchange for a 17.2-billion-U.S.- dollar Asian crisis rescue
package.
</P>
<P>
Sanan is under pressure over the number of houses he owns,
while several close associates of him are under fire for allegedly
building properties encroaching on national parks.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin is also facing opposition accusations that he is
sheltering his brother Sirin, former president of state-run Krung
Thai Bank, from allegations of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
The censure debate began at around 10 a.m., with the opposition
leader and former prime minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh reading a
statement alleging the government's faults.
</P>
<P>
The opposition handed the no-confidence motion against the
government to the House Speaker Wan Muhammad Nor Matha on November
22, the first day of the new parliamentary session.
</P>
<P>
In the motion, the opposition accused the two-year-old
government of economic mismanagement, corruption and ceding the
country's economic sovereignty to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Chuan is said to have set up two special "war rooms" to counter
allegations raised against the coalition, and appeared calm and
controlled before the start of debate.
</P>
<P>
The debates will be focused on the government's economic
performances on the first day, followed by corruption and power
abusing issues, and ethics on the second and third days
respectively.
</P>
<P>
This is the third no-confidence debate against the Democrat-led
six-party coalition, but it is commonly agreed that it will not
threaten stability of the government which enjoys a comfortable
parliamentary majority and does not have to hold election until
October next year.
</P>
<P>
Chuan's coalition commands 236 of the 385 seats in the lower
house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitution, if the Chuan administration
survives the current no-confidence attempt, it will be able to
continue its ruling until the end of its four-year term in
November next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
