<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Bourse to Test for Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE),
one of the two bourses in Bangladesh, will conduct mock automated
trading on December 18 against possible crisis arising out of the
Y2K problem, The Financial Express reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A DSE official was quoted as saying that the hardware and
software providers have assured them of compliance with the
systems to face the millennium bug in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the development, we have planned to conduct a roll-
over test to ensure that nothing will go wrong," DSE chief
executive officer G.Q. Chowdhury said.
</P>
<P>
All the database of the DSE will be preserved in a safe place
and the test run will be conducted by changing the dates to
December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The DSE has a total of 575 terminal and 30 workstations.
Technicians have tested all the personal computers of brokers and
found all the machines are compliant, according to Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
After the roll-over test, the authorities will be in a position
to "judge the effects of Y2K if any," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong Stock Exchange (CSE), the other bourse of the
country, is set to begin mock manual trading, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
