<HEADLINE> Barak, Shareh Arrive in U.S. for Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh arrived in
Washington on Tuesday for the resumption of mideast peace talks
that broke off nearly four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the Dulles International Airport outside the
Washington D.C., Shareh told reporters that his country was
serious about peace and hoped Israel would reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to a productive meeting. We hope we can
pave the way for a peace agreement," Shareh said. "We are serious
about reaching a result. We hope that the Israeli side will
reciprocate our desire for peace."
</P>
<P>
He said Barak's remarks to the Israeli parliament on Monday
made him optimistic about what can be reached during their talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak arrived at Andrews Air Force base on the other side of
Washington about ten minutes later and drove off to Washington
without speaking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks are scheduled to last two days
starting from Wednesday. U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright are expected to watch closely the
whole negotiations, which focus on Israel's withdrawal from the
Golan Heights, security arrangements for Israel and the
normalization of their relations.
</P>
<P>
A National Security Council spokesman said Clinton, Barak and
Shareh are expected to meet at the White House on Wednesday
morning. Then, the Syrian and Israeli delegations plus a U.S.
delegation will hold their negotiation session in the executive
mansion on the west side of the White House.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks are expected to take place at
Blair House, the official guest residence. Albright is expected to
take part in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to meet again with the two leaders at the
White House on Thursday and might make a closing statement,
depending on the outcome of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. official said the administration will do whatever
it can to overcome problems that may occur.
</P>
<P>
"The president has made it very clear that he will do whatever
he can to help in that regard," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
