<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Framework of Macao SAR Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- As a major embodiment of the
principles of "Macao people governing Macao" and "high degree of
autonomy for Macao," the government of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) will be responsible for all
administrative matters of the region except defense and foreign
affairs from the handover of Macao to China on December 20.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law of the Macao SAR, the chief
executive will be the head of the government that consists of
departments, bureaus, offices and sections.
</P>
<P>
The first chief executive of the Macao SAR is Edmund Ho Hau Wah,
who was elected at the third plenary meeting of the Selection
Committee for the First Government of the Macao SAR on May 15,
1999. He was appointed as the chief executive by the State Council
on May 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The first government of the Macao SAR has five departments: the
Department of Administration and Justice, the Department of
Economy and Finance, the Department of Security, the Department of
Social and Cultural Affairs and the Department of Transportation
and Public Projects.
</P>
<P>
The seven principal government officials who have been
appointed include Secretary for Administration and Justice
Florinda da Rosa Silva Chan, Secretary for Economy and Finance
Francis Tam Pak Yuen, Secretary for Security Cheong Kuok Va,
Secretary for Social and Cultural Affairs Fernando Chui Sai On,
Secretary for Transportation and Public Projects Ao Man Long,
Commissioner against Corruption Cheong U and Director of Audit
Fatima Choi Mei Lei.
</P>
<P>
The framework of the government of the Macao SAR was decided at
the sixth plenary meeting of the Preparatory Committee for the
Macao SAR under the National People's Congress (NPC) on March 2,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The State Council appointed the seven principal officials
nominated by the chief executive Edmund Ho Hau Wah on August 11,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The first chief executive and the first government of the Macao
SAR will be sworn in on December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law of the Macao SAR, the principal
officials of the government of the Macao SAR have to be Chinese
citizens among the permanent residents who have been living in
Macao for at least 15 consecutive years. When they assume offices,
the principal officials will have to report their assets to the
judges of the Court of Final Appeal of the Macao SAR for record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
