<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy Predicted to Grow 4 Pct Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia can expect economic
growth of over 4 percent in 2000, higher than the government's
assessment of between 2 and 3.5 percent, an economist of the
Center for Strategic and International Studies Hadi Susastro said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Indonesia attributes the better economic growth
prediction to restored confidence and the prospects for improved
economic growth in the East Asia region.
</P>
<P>
Hadi said that production capacity, which is currently idle,
will have to resume in the year 2000 on the grounds that
international confidence in Indonesia has been restored and that "
this does not need new investment."
</P>
<P>
"Movement in production will encourage our economic growth," he
was quoted by the Indonesian Observer Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the prospects for economic growth in the East Asia
region in 2000 looked good and this would also favorably affect
the Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
But even with the economy growing, he said, the country would
still be burdened with the task of settling various national
issues, including corruption, collusion and nepotism cases.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to continue to settle various national issues
so that a growth of 4 percent can be attained," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the assumption that the inflation rate is expected to be
between 4 and 6 percent, the rate of the rupiah between 6,000 and
7,000 rupiah to the U.S. dollar and the oil price between 16 and
19 U.S. dollars per barrel, Hadi said that these assumptions
should be statically viewed.
</P>
<P>
He cited the planned hike in civil service salaries which is
yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
"The assumption is not static in nature, the increase in civil
salaries will have an impact on other sectors," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Fund Provides Guarantee for Smooth Operation of MSAR Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- By the end of October, the land
fund of the Macao Special Administrative Region(SAR) has exceeded
9.8 billion Patacas, according to a Chinese representative of the
Sino-Portuguese Land Group.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to good management, the land fund suffered no losses
during the Asian financial crisis, instead it reported slight
increase in value, the representative said.
</P>
<P>
According to provisions of Annex II to the Sino-Portuguese
Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao signed by the two
governments in Beijing on April 13, 1987, from the entry into
force of the Joint Declaration until December 19, 1999, all
incomes obtained by the Portuguese Macao government from granting
new leases and renewing leases shall, after deduction of the
average cost of land production, be shared equally by the
Portuguese Macao government and the future government of the Macao
SAR, and the land fund was established as a result.
</P>
<P>
Now, the total land fund of the Macao SAR consists of two parts:
the land income that belongs to the government of the Macao SAR
and all the earnings from the deposits and investments.
</P>
<P>
The money of land fund belongs to the government of the Macao
SAR. It shall be managed by the Chinese Delegation of the Land
Group before the establishment of the government of the Macao SAR.
The management of this fund directly bears on the interests of the
future government of the Macao SAR and those of the residents of
Macao.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Delegation of the Land Group has all along observed
the principles of going about things steadily and surely, avoiding
risks and seeking high returns in the management of the land fund.
In other words, it has tried its best for high returns while
keeping the fund safely intact.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the average yearly return for the land fund was 6.4
percent, higher than the inflation rate publicized by the
Portuguese Macao government. It was not easy to score such
achievement when the financial investment environment was not good
in Macao and in its surrounding areas, especially when Asia was
hit by the financial crisis, the Chinese representative said.
</P>
<P>
The investments made by Macao's land fund have performed well
before Macao's return to China. When the government of the Macao
SAR is set up on December 20, 1999, the land fund will be handed
over by the Central Government to the Macao SAR government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of the Macao Question (1887-1987)(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
January 1955, the Portuguese were forced to halt their
preparations to celebrate "400th anniversary of the opening of
Macao," due to strong protests by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
August 1958, the patriotic Macao Daily News was founded.
</P>
<P>
March 10, 1972, the Chinese government, in a letter to the
United Nations, pointed out that Macao is part of China and has
been occupied by Portugal, and that China will resolve the issue
peacefully by appropriate means when conditions are ripe.
</P>
<P>
April 25, 1974, the new government of Portugal announced that
Macao is not a colony but is Chinese territory under Portuguese
administration.
</P>
<P>
1975, the Portuguese government called back its troops in Macao,
abolished Macao field army and navy commands, and integrated
several police departments to form a unified Macao security force.
</P>
<P>
February 8, 1979, China and Portugal established diplomatic
relations and both sides reiterated that Macao is Chinese
territory under Portuguese administration and that the two
countries will resolve the issue at an appropriate time through
friendly negotiations.
</P>
<P>
June-October, 1986, representatives of the two governments held
the first three rounds of talks on the Macao question in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
March 18-23, 1987, the fourth round of talks was held in
Beijing, at which China and Portugal reached agreement on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
April 13, 1987, China and Portugal formally signed the Sino-
Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Macao Question in the Great
Hall of the People in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
