<HEADLINE> Guizhou Takes Measures to Absorb More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou
Province will grant overseas investors more preferential treatment,
according to a decision made at a recent provincial work
conference.
</P>
<P>
Along with the national policy of exemption of taxation for the
first two years and a tax reduction for another three years,
Guizhou will allow overseas investors to hold a partial share or
the majority of stock of some profitable large and medium-sized
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors also will pay less for the use of land,
electricity, water, and roads. In addition, the local government
will refund taxes levied from foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou has absorbed more than 720 million U.S. dollars of
investment from abroad in the past 10 years, and this year, the
use of foreign investment is to be increased by eight percent
compared with last year's figure. One-fifth of this money came
from developed countries including the United States, Japan, and
Western Europe. 
</P>
