<HEADLINE> Villages in Midair Arouse Interest of Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Two north China villages
located on precipitous cliffs hundreds of meters high have aroused
the interest of folklorists.
</P>
<P>
 Outsiders who want to get into the villages must walk a
mountainous path as dangerous as on a rope. The path is actually
just planks fixed to the mountain side.
</P>
<P>
 The two villages, Wanghuagou and Wuhuashan, are situated in
the heart of Guancen Mountain in Ningwu County, Shanxi Province.
The distance between the two villages is about 2.5 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
 The villagers have small flat spaces dug in cliffs as the
site of their houses which are surrounded by clouds.
</P>
<P>
 Looking up from the foot of the mountain, people feel as
though the villagers are living in midair. The locals also build
their mule and sheep pens on the cliffs.
</P>
<P>
 Although transportation conditions there are harsh and water-
fetching inconvenient, the villagers are reluctant to move to
other places to live as they have become accustomed to this way of
life.
</P>
<P>
 Amazed by these houses hanging in the air, some folklore
experts asked the villagers when those houses were built, but no
one could answer.
</P>
<P>
 After a recent fact-finding tour, the folklorists said these
villages are truly of great value for further study.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
