<HEADLINE> Macao Readying for December 20 Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Macao, which is to end its long
separation from China and return home on December 20, is readying
itself for the grand handover ceremony and carnival-style
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Facilities for a series of major events are ready or almost
ready. These include a ship-like seaside structure, where the
handover ceremony is to be held; the Forum with Chinese-style
decoration, where President Jiang Zemin of China is to declare the
establishment of the Macao Special Administrative Region (MSAR)
and where the government of the MSAR will be inaugurated; and a
building complex housing the Foreign Ministry Commissioner's
Office.
</P>
<P>
Above the front gate of the Commissioner's Office is a giant
national emblem of the People's Republic of China covered by a
piece of red cloth. In the early morning of December 20, the
national emblem will be unveiled and, at the same time, all
symbols of Portuguese rule in Macao will disappear here, for ever.
</P>
<P>
There are other signs of what Macao people are doing for the
historic handover. The streets are filled with a festive mood.
Shops, hotels and residential buildings are decorated with posters
and colorful banners that carry slogans welcoming the upcoming
return of Macao to its motherland.
</P>
<P>
Lew Yim Kuen, a local youngster, said, "Our heart is already
home."
</P>
<P>
For officials designate of the MSAR government, December,
normally a month of holidays, is becoming busier than ever as the
day to start implementing the principle of "Macao people governing
Macao" draws near. This is true of celebration organizers of
various circles and more than 4,000 local police officers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, telecom and power-supply departments have worked out
plans to ensure the success of all handover-related activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
