<HEADLINE> Dismissed Romanian Prime Minister Chooses to Return to Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Dismissed Romanian Prime
Minister Radu Vasile appeared Tuesday to have accepted his ouster
by President Emil Constantinescu, saying that he would return to
the senate "in the national interest."
</P>
<P>
Vasile said late Tuesday that he has decided to return to the
senate "to be an ordinary senator" and that he does not want to
see the crisis last long.
</P>
<P>
Vasile, who was sacked by the president early Tuesday after
major parties in the ruling coalition withdrew support for him,
said he would not go to the constitutional court over the
justification of his dismissal, but adding that he would not
announce his resignation either.
</P>
<P>
Vasile had first refused to accept his removal, which he called
"unconstitutional," and vowed to take this to the constitutional
court.
</P>
<P>
The crisis caused by the prime minister's ouster has stirred up
strong reaction from the media as well as the political forum of
Romania.
</P>
<P>
Most opposition parties and many legal experts have questioned
the authority of the president to dismiss Vasile.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition Social Democratic Party said in a
statement that under the constitution only parliament has the
right to sack the prime minister. It demanded the president
withdraw his decision.
</P>
<P>
Former President and the party's Chairman Ion Iliescu called
for a technocrat government to guide the country and prepare for
next year's general elections.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Vasile's acceptance of his removal might
bring an early end to the political standoff. 
</P>
