<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Enjoy Final Adjudication Power After Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Macao Special Administrative
Region (SAR) will enjoy the independent judicial power, including
that of final adjudication, after China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over Macao beginning from zero hours on December 20
when judges of the courts at all levels of Macao SAR officially
swear in.
</P>
<P>
Macao, without independent judicial power for a long time, only
has the court of first instance, and all the appeal cases must be
submitted to the intermediate courts in Lisbon. The final
adjudication power belongs to the Supreme Court of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese laws defines the qualifications of Macao judges, who
are appointed by a supreme commission of Portuguese judges. The
setup, functions, operation principles and legal procedures are
all defined by the Portuguese legislation.
</P>
<P>
Following the signing of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration,
Portugal revised relevant articles concerning Macao in its
Constitution and the Organic Statute of Macao, which granted Macao
with greater legislative and judicial autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The Superior Tribunal of Justice of Macao that was established
in April 1993 is Macao's highest level court, which is responsible
for the second hearing and re-examination of the cases submitted
by the courts of first instance.
</P>
<P>
The existing courts in Macao handle most of the cases of Macao,
but they do not enjoy the fully independent judicial power. Some
of the cases, such as those civil and criminal cases involving the
Macao Governor or Assistant Secretary, must be submitted to a
court in Lisbon. Some of the appeal cases, especially those
involving president of the Legislative Assembly, anti-corruption
Commissioners and judges of the Superior Tribunal of Justice, must
be submitted to the Supreme Court of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
The Macao SAR will enjoy independent judicial power including
that of final adjudication after the Chinese government resumes
the exercise of sovereignty over Macao.
</P>
<P>
The courts of Macao SAR shall have complete and exclusive power
of adjudication over all cases in the region, except matters
concerning acts of State such as defence and foreign affairs. No
instruction issued by the Supreme Court of the People's Republic
of China shall have binding force on the region. The Macao SAR
will have primary courts, intermediate courts and the Court of
Final Appeal. The Basic Law of the Macao SAR grants its power of
final adjudication to the Court of Final Appeal.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of nomination of an independent committee
responsible for recommending judges, Macao SAR's First Chief
Executive-designate Edmund Ho Hau Wah announced on October 7 of
this year the name list of judges of the Macao SAR courts at
various levels, including three judges of the Court of Final
Appeal.
</P>
<P>
These judges, who will be officially appointed on December 20,
will carry out the Macao SAR Basic Law, the principles of "one
country, two systems," "Macao people governing Macao," and a high
degree of autonomy, and safeguard the independent judicial power,
including that of final adjudication.
</P>
<P>
Functions and power of the Macao SAR courts, especially that of
the Court of Final Appeal, will be defined by the Organic Law of
the Macao SAR Judicial System which is under formulation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0281 </DOCNO>
