<HEADLINE> South China's Guangxi Reports Higher Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region expects an eight percent economic growth rate
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the autonomous region will
accomplish 200 billion yuan (24 billion US dollars) in gross
domestic product (GDP) for all services and products generated in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi's fast economic growth is attributed to the central
government's policy to spur domestic demand and the expansion of
reform in state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Local industrial enterprises have been doing well since the
beginning of the year, and reported profits for the first time in
three years.
</P>
<P>
In the first ten months of this year, the comprehensive index
of the autonomous region's industrial economic benefit was 73.9
percent, up 13.7 percentage points over the same period last year.
Small industrial enterprises in the region realized profits of 55
million yuan (6.6 million US dollars), and large and medium-sized
state-owned or controlled industrial enterprises realized 78
million yuan (9.4 million US dollars) in profits.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, more money recently has been invested in
improving the region's infrastructure. A total of 155 capital
construction projects requiring an aggregate state investment of
67.2 billion yuan in Guangxi have been included in the state plan.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has also pumped more investment into
capital construction. And more flood control facilities and major
embankments along the coast are now finished, coupled with
completion of a number of water control and ecological projects,
all of which have helped improved the region's capacity to combat
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The living environment and quality of life for urban residents
in Guangxi have improved enormously as more investment has been
spent to build transportation, water and gas supply, and trash and
sewage treatment projects in urban areas of the region, said local
sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
