<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Birds in China Under Greater Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- While walking in the fields
two weeks ago, two farmers living in the Taihang Mountains in
north China discovered a big bird with an injured wing.
</P>
<P>
To save the bird, they took it home and reported their
discovery to a local forestry department, which told them the bird
was a grey crane under second-class state.
</P>
<P>
The department contacted wildlife protection personnel and the
bird was sent to a zoo in Taiyuan, capital of Shanxi Province, for
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
As winter sets in, large flocks of birds begin to fly south.
However, weak and wounded birds usually lagged behind their
brothers and sisters in migration.
</P>
<P>
More often than not, people in the province will feed and
treat wounded birds and contact wildlife departments, and some 60
rare birds such as the grey crane, swan, wild geese, and wild
ducks have been saved in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
But not everyone is a good Samaritans. Seeking profit, some
persons unlawfully hunt the birds in Shanxi and then try to
smuggled them overseas. To cope with this problem, the police have
strengthened their crackdown on the poaching activities.
</P>
<P>
On November 9, police in the city of Houma in Shanxi Province
discovered in three bamboo baskets holding 17 owls, three of which
were dead.
</P>
<P>
The pest-eating owls living in the forests of the Taihang and
Luliang mountains are under strict protection. But an owl can
fetch as much as 1,000 U.S. dollars on the black market.
</P>
<P>
The police have sent 14 living owls to a wildlife protection
center, and they continue to hunt down illegal traders.
</P>
<P>
In another incident, police in Taiyuan recently impounded on a
vehicle on a highway which held 12 eagles that are under second-
class state protection, and three suspects were arrested.
</P>
<P>
At present, the eagles are recovering after rehabilitation at
a zoo in Taiyuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi Province is not the only place where people are paying
greater attention to protecting birds. Tianjin Municipality in
north China, which has 235 kinds of birds, is doing a good job as
well.
</P>
<P>
Since early 1982, a "loving birds week" is arranged every year
in the port city to increase people's awareness of wildlife
protection, and residents in the city have set up five wildlife
centers.
</P>
<P>
Police in Tianjin have resorted to stern measures against
poachers, illicit bird traders, and restaurant owners who
illegally purchase bird meat.
</P>
<P>
As a result, official surveys have found that the number of
birds and bird species are both increasing year by year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outlook on U.S. Life Insurance Industry Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Standard &AMP; Poor's has
revised its outlook for the U.S. life insurance industry to
negative from stable.
</P>
<P>
The global ratings service said that the revision reflects its
view that pressures affecting the industry and the industry's
attempts to confront those pressures over the next few years will
leave the industry weaker at the end of that period than it is
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the service's outlook report released Tuesday, the
overriding influence that will have a negative effect on ratings
will be the pressure on the industry by the capital markets to
attain greater efficiency in its deployment of capital.
</P>
<P>
"Either earnings will have to improve to better serve the
existing capital of the industry or capital will have to be
reduced so that what remains is better served by existing earnings,
" the report said. The service believes that most insurance
companies will pursue a strategy involving a combination of both
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
As financial convergence runs its course, the report said, life
insurance companies will increasingly be compared in their
profitability to other types of financial institutions. But life
companies generally do not look good in such comparisons.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the report said, the industry has built its
capital position to historically high levels, contributing to
lower returns on equity. Many companies have sustained their
financial strength ratings with an over-abundance of capital.
Such positions have been sustained, in part, because of the
continuing dominance of the mutual form of ownership in the
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
