<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Predicts New Record Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Agriculture
Minister Vinicius Pratini de Moraes said Tuesday that the next
Brazilian harvest of 1999-2000 will set a new record of 83.4
million tons, 1.2 percent increase over the 1998-1999 period.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that the cultivated land will be 36.9 million
hectares, up 0.5 percent from the same period, according to local
press.
</P>
<P>
Further increase of cultivated land will be possible, suggested
the minister, in spite of the drop in international prices to the
lowest level over the past 30 years, and the drought in the
southern and southeastern regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister highlighted in particular the country's steady
growth rate of agricultural productivity, which has been
maintained at four percent in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
He predicted the agricultural sector, with the exception of
agro-industry, to grow at six percent this year, accounting for
nine percent of Brazil's Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
He estimated an 11.8 billion dollar surplus in the sector this
year, and expected for 2000 a 15 billion dollar surplus, mainly
guaranteed by the improvement in the international prices and in
more added value to fruits exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
