<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Minister on Challenges of Power Sector Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, U.S., December 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria Tuesday said that
challenges should be handled in reforming the nation's power
sector in order to carry out the government's firm commitment to
the provision of reliable electricity to all consumers in the West
African country.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian minister of power and steel, Bola Ige, told a
plenary session of the three-day U.S.-Africa Energy Ministers
Conference that "The government is committed to an enabling
environment which guarantees level ground competition to make free
power market thrive in Nigeria and will do everything possible to
ensure that costs of operation and unnecessary tolls are reduced
to barest minimum."
</P>
<P>
"The Federal Government is establishing a new power policy
within a national energy policy and will subsequently create a new
power trade and free market within Nigeria and promote same in the
West African sub-region," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, "Government is fully aware of the responsibility that
this goal bears as well as the various factors militating against
its moves and it has enough political will and strength to combat
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian minister, who assumed his office after the May 29
Swear-in of Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo in the wake of a
successful transition to civilian rule in the country, listed
seven major challenges in reforming the country's power sector.
</P>
<P>
They are: need for immediate action, restructuring of existing
power company, restructuring the power sector, provision of
enabling environment, creation of infrastructure, developing a
national transmission grid, and surmounting social problems.
</P>
<P>
The oil-rich Nigeria is the most populous country in Africa,
and it has been long under the military rule since its
independence from the British colonial rule in October 1960. The
election of Obasanjo as its civilian president put an end to the
military rule and marked a return to the civilian rule in the West
African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
