<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Cyclists Reported Taking Dope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Blood tests on some of the world'
s top cyclists showed they had taken dangerous performance-
enhancing chemicals, according to a prosecutor's report sent to
the Italian Olympic committee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tests were carried out as part of an investigation by
Bologna prosecutors into the sale, prescription and administration
of harmful pharmaceuticals to sportsmen and women.
</P>
<P>
In May, indictments were requested for 16 doctors and sports
managers accused of damaging athletes' health by having them take
dangerous pharmaceuticals and hormones.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Olympic Committee, Coni, asked to see the results
of the tests in order to consider possible disciplinary action
against the individual athletes, even though they are considered
as victims in the Bologna probe.
</P>
<P>
The investigation involves top level cyclists, including
Italians Mario Cipollini, Ivan Gotti, Paolo Salvodelli and other
big international names such as Pavel Tonkov, Abraham Olano and
Axel Merckx.
</P>
<P>
Gotti was the controversial winner of this year's Giro d'Italia.
He took the title after Marco Pantani, the runaway leader, was
suspended because of a dangerously high red blood cell count.
</P>
<P>
The list of names delivered to Coni also contains some former
cyclists such as Claudio Chiappucci, Tony Rominger, Ferdinando
Escartin and Armand De Las Cuevas.
</P>
<P>
"Certain blood readings, such as haematocrit and ferratin,
represented a danger for the cyclists' health," said one of
consultants called in to conduct tests.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't a case of natural variations, but of alterations due
to the taking of various substances," he continued.
</P>
<P>
One of the 16 people for whom prosecutors have requested
indictments is Michele Ferrari, a doctor paid for his services by
Gotti, Cipollini, Tonkov and Savoldelli among others.
</P>
<P>
Ferrari stands accused of giving cyclists growth hormones and
substances like EPO - technical name eritropoietine - which
thickens the blood by increasing the number of oxygen carrying red
corpuscles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wembley Faces Rival Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- A late bid to oust Wembley as
the site of the new national stadium is being formed by a
consortium of top contractors.
</P>
<P>
The organisation London International Stadium wants to build a
150,000 seater facility in Hillingdon, a borough off the A40 route
into west London.
</P>
<P>
The proposal coincides with confirmation from Wembley National
Stadium Ltd and UK Athletics that a bid to host the 2005 World
Athletics Championships at Wembley can go ahead.
</P>
<P>
Sir Norman Foster's design for the new Wembley stadium was
originally rejected by the government because consultants Ellerbe
Becket said it failed to make adequate provision for the staging
of athletics events.
</P>
<P>
The Hillingdon stadium is understood to include retractable
seats that make it suitable for both athletics and football, as
well as a sliding roof - features missing from the new Wembley.
</P>
<P>
The Hillingdon consortium also believes it can build its
national stadium for 300 million pounds, which is a massive 175
million pounds cheaper than Foster's building.
</P>
<P>
Consultant Gary Francis said: "We are confident we can be ready
to open in 2004 allowing a year for the planning and consultative
stage.
</P>
<P>
"The area is served by three tube lines and a mainline station
that goes to Marylebone, but could be extended into Paddington as
the track runs parallel.
</P>
<P>
"We are only 15 minutes from Heathrow. To reach the stadium you
wouldn't have to go through any residential areas and there are
plans for a six lane link road to the stadium off the A40."
</P>
<P>
He argued that Wembley was "so difficult to get to" and"
historical reasons" were not good enough to keep the stadium there.
</P>
<P>
"On our site you could have a great stadium any size you want
and with Brunel University nearby you have a campus that would be
suitable for an Olympic village," said Francis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
