<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chevron to Make West African Gas Pipeline Operational in Late 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, U.S., December 14 (Xinhua) -- Chevron, one of the world
's largest energy and chemical companies, Tuesday told Xinhua that
the company is scheduled to complete the construction of one of
West Africa's most significant regional energy project, the West
African Gas Pipeline (WAGP), in late 2000 and make the project
operational in late 2002.
</P>
<P>
Chris Miller, Chevron's project manager who is in charge of
the work on WAGP, said that after a series of feasibility studies
and legal environment studies, "Chevron plans to finish the WAGP
construction in the fourth quarter of 2000, and the pipeline is
expected to be operational in late 2000."
</P>
<P>
In a joint venture agreement signed on August 16 in the
Nigerian capital of Abuja, Chevron has been appointed project
manager for WAGP. The joint venture agreement establishes a
consortium of six energy resources companies to develop WAGP,
outlines the corporate structure of the joint venture and
establishes a program to expedite the technical and commercial
activities required to complete pipeline development by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The consortium and the governments of Benin, Ghana, Nigeria
and Togo signed a Memorandum of Understanding on August 11,
granting development rights to the consortium.
</P>
<P>
The 965-kilometer pipeline, is expected to cost about 400
million U.S. dollars and to initially ship some 120 million cubic
feet per day of Nigerian gas for sale to power-generation
customers in Benin, Ghana and Togo, he said.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we do not have any difficulties in doing this project,
" he said. "The three parties, the governments, the pipeline
consortium and the customers, all see the benefit of the project."
</P>
<P>
In addition to delivering much needed energy to West African
countries, it is envisioned that the project will significantly
contribute to the economies of the participating nations through
the creation of jobs and low-cost fuel for new industrial and
commercial development ventures, he said. "Responding to these new
demands, the volumes may double or triple over the life of the
project."
</P>
<P>
The WAGP project will reduce greenhouse-gas emissions by
cutting down on flaring associated with existing oil production in
Nigeria, an oil-rich country in the world. Air pollutants will be
further reduced because natural gas will replace the use of fuel
that are less "friendly" to the environment in power generation
and industrial production, he said.
</P>
<P>
Also participating in the projects are companies from Nigeria,
Ghana and Togo.
</P>
<P>
Operating in Africa since 1930s, Chevron has been working with
the nations of Africa to develop, refine and market their
hydrocarbon resources. At present, the company is doing business
in more than 90 countries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
From its headquarters in San Francisco, California in the
United States, Chevron's global operations extend to all realms of
the energy business -- from oil and gas exploration and production
to refining and marketing, petrochemicals, logistics and trading,
and shipping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Solidarity Commission Approves Budgets for Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Olympic Solidarity
Commission has approved the Olympic Solidarity budget for 2000 for
a total amount of 31 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The commission, chaired by the International Olympic Committee
President Juan Antonio Samaranch, also approved a special budget
of 21,3 million dollars to help the National Olympic Committees (
NOCs) with their participation in and contribution to the success
of the Olympic Games in Sydney, according to an IOC press release
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The IOC said that these funds are aimed at assisting a
determined number of athletes and officials to be present at the
Olympic Games as well as to help the NOCs to develop their
structures and programmes.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the participants at the commission's meeting on
Monday approved the arrangements of two meetings in 2000. The
first one will be held in Rio de Janeiro, during the Association
of National Olympic Committees (ANOC) General Assembly in May.
</P>
<P>
The second one will take place in Sydney just before the
Olympic Games start. During this meeting the Olympic Solidarity
will present for approval the objectives, programmes and budget
for the 2001-2004 quadrennial.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic Solidarity is the arm of the IOC responsible for
redistributing the share of the revenue generated by the sale of
broadcast rights of the Olympic Games to the NOCs to help them
develop their local sports infrastructure and train athletes,
coaches, and administrators. 
</P>
