<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Council Delays Vote on Iraq Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- At the request of
France, the United Nations Security Council on Tuesday once again
delayed its vote on a draft resolution on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. diplomats, France delayed the vote, saying
it needs more time to consider its position on the draft
resolution which has been under contentious debate for months
among the 15-member Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution seeks to create a U.N. weapons inspection
regime for Iraq and it would suspend sanctions if Iraq cooperates
with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Council president for the current month
Jeremy Greenstock of Britain said he had reported to the Council
that at the request of one Council member for more time, the
scheduling of the formal vote has been postponed. He gave no new
date for the vote.
</P>
<P>
Alain Dejammet, France"s Ambassador to the United Nations said
earlier that Paris wanted more clarity on the so-called "trigger
mechanism" that sets criteria for the sanctions suspension.
</P>
<P>
Changes have been made on the key section over the last twenty-
four hours but it is still too vague to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have been pressing for the vote
on the draft resolution for several days, an apparent attempt to
revive U.N. arms regime for Iraq at an earlier date which was met
with rejection from some members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
 It is widely seen here that if the draft resolution was
adopted, it would start a complicated new process on weapons
inspection and humanitarian program.
</P>
<P>
U.N. weapons inspectors withdrew from Iraq days before the U.S.
-led military strikes against the country last December. Iraq has
barred them from returning unless the stringent U.N. sanctions get
lifted.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. According to relevant U.N. resolutions, Iraq must
be free of weapons of mass destruction before the sanctions can be
lifted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
