<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. Government 99.9 Percent Y2K-Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday that all but a handful of the government's most
important computer systems are prepared for the New Year's date
change.
</P>
<P>
"As of today, 99.9 percent of the government's mission critical
computer systems are Y2K compliant," Clinton said in a statement
accompanying a report on the issue by the White House Office of
Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
The administration said only 16 of the government's 6,159 most
important systems are not prepared for the Y2K rollover, and those
others will be ready later this month.
</P>
<P>
The government said it will have spent 8.38 billion U.S.
dollars on the massive project, an increase of 37 million dollars
from September's estimate, which it attributed to higher last-
minute testing costs.
</P>
<P>
"We have met the deadline, and we have done it at below cost,"
Clinton said. He cautioned that "no amount of preparation can
prevent us from glitches," but assured Americans that backup plans
are ready.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's top Y2K adviser, John Koskinen, also cautioned that
glitches are inevitable, even in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Not every system will be fixed, and even some of those that
have been fixed and tested may experience glitches," he said.
</P>
<P>
Their remarks came as the Office of Management and Budget
released its final report on the government's efforts, saying
those 16 systems yet to be repaired are in the Defense and Justice
departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
