<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy at Forefront in Renewable Energy in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Italy is at the forefront of
research and development into alternative sources of energy and
can rightly show the rest of Europe the way forward, Italian
industry Minister Pierluigi Bersani said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference held by Enea, the national council for
nuclear and alternative energies, Bersani cited statistics showing
the steady development of alternative forms of energy in Italy
over the last ten years.
</P>
<P>
"On a European level Italy holds a leading position in the area
of renewable energy," he said, "This sector has been handled in
exactly the right way."
</P>
<P>
According to Enea, in 1998 some 17 million Petrol Equivalent
Tons(PET) of energy were produced from renewable energy sources.
</P>
<P>
This accounted for 9 percent of national consumption and
followed a decade of annual growth averaging 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The slice of Italy's electrical energy deriving from renewable
sources was almost 17 percent of the national demand and had grown
by 2.6 percent a year since 1990, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was also progress in wind power, which had gone from zero
to 51,000 PET a year since 1990, and in bio-combustible fuels,
which were up from zero to 81,000 PET a year over the same period.
</P>
<P>
But hydroelectric power and the simple burning of wood and its
derivatives continued to account for the lion's share of the
alternative fuel supply, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Hydroelectric power supplied to the national grid rose from 7.
49 million PET in 1989 to 9.07 million in 1998, while wood
remained constant at about 6.4 million PET. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
