<HEADLINE> U.S. Vows to Aid Africa in Sustainable Energy Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, U.S., December 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Government
Tuesday said that it will work hard to help African nations with
sustainable development, which means to tap the potential of its
rich energy resources while paying close attention to
environmental protection on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a key-note speech at the plenary session of the
three-day U.S.-Africa Energy Ministers Conference, which kicked
off here on Monday evening, Bill Richardson, the U.S. secretary of
energy, said that, "Though we gather from different points on the
globe, we share a commitment to Africa, to its sustainable energy
development, its integration into the world marketplace, and its
overall prosperity."
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, energy ministers from the United States
and Africa are convening on a continent-wide basis to discuss
Africa's energy future, and the future of the energy partnership
between the U.S. and Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
The current conference attracts some 50 African energy
ministers and 450 representatives from governments, industrial and
financial realms and international organizations and private
sector.
</P>
<P>
"For Africa, sustainable energy development would enhance
prosperity, diminish poverty and liberate resources for essentials
such as health services," he said. "This conference is a
cornerstone of my African Energy Initiative to foster energy
cooperation and sustainable development in Africa into the next
century and beyond."
</P>
<P>
On the basis the U.S.-Africa Partnership Plan put forward by U.
S. President Bill Clinton, Richardson has raised the initiative in
a bid to strengthen the ties between America and Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We will work with countries and regional organizations in
Africa, and the Agency for International Development, the Trade
and Development Agency, the Small Business Administration, the
Overseas Private Investment Corporation and the Export Import Bank
" to carry out the initiative, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the energy development must be kept within the
framework of the environmental protection. "As you know, burning
fossil fuels and wood produces greenhouse gases," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
