<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 32.42 at 11,160.17,
expanding its loss of 32.11 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 12.05 at 1,403.17 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 86.51 at 3,571.66.
</P>
<P>
The stocks fell after the Commerce Department reported that
retail sales rose 0.9 percent in November, the largest increase in
three months. Investors feared that the report may prompt the
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates to ward off inflation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Labor Department said its Consumer Price Index
rose just 0.1 percent in November, its most modest showing in five
months. But investors focused on the retail sales rise and worried
about the rate hike.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised rates three times this year to
cool off the U.S. economy in an effort to keep inflation under
control. But stocks have raced higher as well as more consumer
spending.
</P>
<P>
Investors believed that the Federal Reserve would raise rates
again to cool off the economy due to steep rise in consumer price.
But analysts said it will not happen at the next Federal Reserve
meeting on December 21 because of concerns with Y2K problem and
the Federal Reserve may raise the rates as early as next February.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking also helped to drag stocks lower. Investors pull
money of the market to lock in profits from recent strong rallies
of technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 4.44 at 632.07 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 0.91 at 827.78. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 7.58 at 462.80.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,085 down, 1,048 up and 437
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.02 billion shares from 971.01
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
