<HEADLINE> Maskhadov Says Ready for Dialogue With Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 14 (Xinhua) -- President Aslan Maskhadov of
Russia's breakaway republic of Chechnya said Tuesday that he is
ready to meet federal leaders and Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Chairman Knut Vollebaek.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov promised to guarantee the safety of Russian and OSCE
officials in the areas under his control, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek, who is also foreign minister of Norway, said earlier
Tuesday while touring neighboring Daghestan that the OSCE is ready
to join mediation efforts to end the fighting in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
But Russian First Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander Adveyev
said Moscow does not need help from international organizations in
resolving the conflict, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE could use its international influence in aiding Russia
's anti-terrorist operation in Chechnya by calling on all
countries not to support Chechen terrorists, Aveyev said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a lack of go-betweens in the conflict but the
absence of an influential Chechen who could hold talks on behalf
of the republic," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We feel that our colleagues in the West underestimate the
danger of terrorism. Our units in Chechnya are defending the whole
of Europe from the danger of terrorism as well as Russia's
integrity."
</P>
<P>
Russia launched the current military campaign against Chechen
rebels in September following their armed incursion into
neighboring Daghestan and a spate of terrorist bombings, also
blamed on the rebels, that killed about 300 people in Moscow and
two other Russian cities. 
</P>
