<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. Continues to Commit to Panama Canal's Security (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday that the U.S. will continue its commitment to the
Panama Canal's security and the transfer of the canal to Panama
underscores U.S. confidence in Panama's ability to manage the
canal.
</P>
<P>
A transfer ceremony was held in Panama Tuesday, but Clinton
and other senior U.S. officials failed to attend it.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton said the U.S. will continue to
"work closely with Panama to safeguard the canal and promote the
well-being of our citizens and people around the world."
</P>
<P>
"Today's ceremony underscores our confidence in the government
of Panama and the Panamanian people's ability to manage this vital
artery of commerce," he added.
</P>
<P>
"It also signals our continuing commitment to the security of
the canal, as enshrined in our treaty obligations, and our
determination to work with Panama and the many other countries
that use the canal to ensure that it remains open to the world's
shipping and commerce," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
After the transfer, the canal will be run by the Canal
Authority, an autonomous institution created with the consensus of
all political parties in Panama.
</P>
<P>
"At the edge of a new century, the canal, long a symbol of
American power and prestige, now also symbolizes the unity and
common purpose of the democratic nations of the Americas," Clinton
added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vice President Al Gore is busy at his campaign to replace
Clinton in 2000, and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
stay at home to push the Israel-Syria peace talks. The U.S.
delegation was headed by Former President Jimmy Carter, who signed
the treaties with Panama in 1977 to turn over the canal to Panama.
</P>
<P>
However, White House spokesman said that the U.S. is "well
represented at this ceremony." "We have a number of Cabinet
officers there," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, speaking at a regular White House briefing,
rejected suggestions that the absence of senior U.S. officials
from the ceremony was linked to conservative criticism of the
transfer as the presidential campaign starts next year.
</P>
<P>
"I think some of the somewhat hysterical comments coming from
the right, notwithstanding, that seek to distort the record, just
have to be ignored, as is often times the best way to deal with
some comments," Lockhart said. "Our commitment to that region of
the world is unparalleled by any president."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lockhart said that the absence does not indicate "
any lower estimation" of Panama.
</P>
<P>
"We have an important relationship with Panama. We've worked
closely with them over the last 22 years to reach this day,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the president has taken 12 foreign trips this
year. "That puts a heavy load on both the president and the staff.
"
</P>
<P>
"There are many trips that he wants to take that he believes
are important that we just can't do. This fits that category. So
this decision was not made based on the politics," the spokesman
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
