<HEADLINE> Panama to Guarantee Canal Security: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian President
Mireya Moscoso said Tuesday that her country will guarantee the
efficient, secure, and competitive functioning of the interoceanic
waterway.
</P>
<P>
"We achieved the victory, the canal is ours," said Moscoso in a
speech after the exchange of letters of understanding for the
delivery of the Canal with former U.S. president Jimmy Carter, who
represented the Washington government.
</P>
<P>
Panama is walking toward the perfecting of its biggest wealth,
its strategic geographical position in world trade, she said.
</P>
<P>
The United States will hand over the Canal to Panama and will
withdraw its troops from the interoceanic waterway, according to
the 1977 Torrijos-Carter treaties.
</P>
<P>
The responsibility of administering in an efficient and secure
way the Panama Canal will be exclusive of the Panama Republic and
of Panamanians, which will be done without any kind of political
involvement, she said.
</P>
<P>
Moscoso said that the long term goal is to make the waterway a
world class leading enterprise, at the competitive service of the
international maritime community.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian president said that to achieve this goal, Panama
needs the support of the developed countries and the solidarity of
the Iberoamerican countries.
</P>
<P>
Moscoso and Carter exchanged the letters of understanding
during a ceremony in the floodgates of Miraflores before six Latin
American heads of state and the king Juan Carlos. Not any high-
ranking U.S. official attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Latin American presidents present at the ceremony were
Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico,Jamil Mahuad of Ecuador, Carlos Roberto
Flores of Honduras, Hugo Banzer of Bolivia, Andres Pastrana of
Colombia, and Miguel Angel Rodriguez of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five years of United States colonialism in the so-called
Panama Canal Zone ended with the exchange of two letters of
understanding signed Tuesday by Carter and President Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
Carter signed in 1977 as U.S. president the agreement for the
handover of the Canal with then Panamanian government head General
Omar Torrijos, who died in an air accident in 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
