<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Peace Talks adjourn at UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The proximity talks
between the two parties of Cyprus adjourned Tuesday after twelve
days during which both parties have engaged very seriously with
the whole range of issues that divided them.
</P>
<P>
The talks were undertaken between Glafcos Clerides, President
of Cyprus and the leader of the Greek Cypriots, and Rauf Denktash,
the leader of the Turkish Cypriots which began on December 3 at
the Headquarters of the United Nations in New York.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press, U.N. Secretary-General's special advisor
on Cyprus Alvaro de Soto said the talks would resume early next
year.
</P>
<P>
Soto said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan had invited the two
parties to resume the talks on the same basis next year and the
date would be announced in due course. He gave no details on the
talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. brokered proximity talks mean that Clerides and
Denktash are within reach other but do not meet face to face, and
U.N. coordinators shuttle between them.The talks are aimed to
prepare the ground for the later direct talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
