<DOCNO> XIE19991215.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Transfer is Historical Fact for L. America: Carter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Former United States
President Jimmy Carter said here Tuesday that the transfer of the
Panama Canal to the isthmus country is a historical fact for all
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The transfer ceremony was held Tuesday in the Panamanian
capital and had a numerous international attendance, among them
six Latin American heads of state and King Juan Carlos of Spain.
</P>
<P>
The six presidents who attended the ceremony were Ernesto
Zedillo of Mexico, Jamil Mahuad of Ecuador, Carlos Flores of
Honduras, Hugo Banzer of Bolivia, Andres Pastrana of Colombia, and
Miguel Angel Rodriguez of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
"We are witnessing a historic protocolary act, very important
for all the Latin American countries," said the former U.S.
president.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five years of United States colonialism in the Zone of
the Canal of Panama ended with the exchange of letters of
understanding, signed by Carter and Panamanian President Mireya
Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
However, Carter warned that the United States has the right and
the duty to defend the Panama Canal from external threats that
imperil the security of the interoceanic waterway after the
handover of the canal on December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"But it has been agreed that this will be always done jointly,
with the cooperation and at the request of Panama, if this were
necessary.
</P>
<P>
"Let me tell you that Panama has inherited not only the canal,
but also some challenges, because there is always the menace of
drug traffic, and there is a serious threat for the environment,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Carter ended his speech by saying that this is a marvelous
opportunity for the United States to recognize the excellent
potentiality of the canal, not only for Panama, but also for the
United States and all the countries of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
