<HEADLINE> London Stock Ends Lower For Two Straight Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- London Stock ended lower
Tuesday for the second straight session after a see-saw day
dominated by transport and financial stocks.
</P>
<P>
The index dipped just 8.6 points to finish at 6702.1, keeping
the benchmark within 70 points of its intraday peak of 6772.1 set
on December 3.
</P>
<P>
The main loser was the drug sector, with heavyweight GLXO down
2 percent and rivals AZN and SB- falling 2.5 percent and 5 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, the Railtrack stock soared 9 percent, and was pursued
higher by shipping and logistics firm PO- and British Airways.
</P>
<P>
NWB, the subject of competing hostile bids from Bank of
Scotland and Royal Bank of Scotland rose 1 percent, while the Bank
of Scotland gained 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Dax closed at an all-time high, one percent firmer on
the day, or 61 points, to 6187.99. The index had peaked at 6247.24
earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
Paris CAC 40 gained 28.7 points to 5564.47. It is the 34th
record close for the market 1999, boosted by France Telecom and
other blue-chip stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
