<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Puts Off Visits to Jordan, Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema
Tuesday postponed a scheduled trip to Jordan and Israel next week
because of the political situation at home.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema was due to visit the two countries from December 20 to
23, but the recent rise of tensions within the ruling center-left
alliance has compelled him to verify whether he still has a
working majority.
</P>
<P>
He is due to address the Lower House at the end of the week,
probably Saturday, after the passage of the budget bill, and has
said he may offer to stand down unless his speech receives the
necessary backing from all the components of his 12-party
coalition.
</P>
<P>
The situation came to a head Monday when D'Alema offered to
resign immediately after repeated attacks on his leadership from
the tiny Democratic Socialist party.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Socialists and others in the coalition say the
alliance must change leaders to have a chance of winning the next
general election, which must come by spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema Monday received the strong backing of his party, and
was also advised by President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi to postpone the
political reckoning until after the budget vote.
</P>
<P>
Observers in the press expect one of the outcomes of Thursday's
debate could be a resignation only for D'Alema to be reassigned
the premiership after a reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Another could be a snap election although that is considered
less likely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
